Name: Manatee 360
Overview: Manatee 360 is an immersive virtual reality experience that will take you below the surface of Florida's fresh-water springs and into the home of these iconic and lovable sea mammals. See the world from the manatee's point of view as we learn about their daily lives and habits and current threats to their tenuous existence. Find out about some of the conservation efforts focused on ensuring manatee survival in an ever changing and increasingly endangered habitat while spending a few minutes surrounded by these gentle, inquisitive, peace-loving giants. Manatee 360 encourages us to love and care about these amazing animals by bringing us into their world in a totally new and fully engaging way.

Name: Pika 360
Overview: Pika 360 is an immersive experience that takes you to the summits of the Rocky Mountains. Experience the soaring vistas of the fragile, alpine ecosystem that the American pika calls home, while getting eye to eye with the world's cutest mammal as he goes about his daily life. Learn about those who are helping protect this small but invaluable member of our earthly community. Then find out how we can join in the fight to save them, and in doing so, how we might also save ourselves.

Name: Wolverine 360
Overview: Wolverine 360 is an immersive virtual reality experience that will introduce you to one of the world's toughest, yet charismatic, creatures. Requiring vast tracts of wilderness to thrive, wolverines inhabit some of the most inhospitable terrain on the planet and avoid human development, yet they have a softer side. Travel to Alaska to learn about the importance of wolverines and current threats to their tenuous existence from one of the only people to rescue and raise wolverines in captivity, Steve Kroschel. Wolverine 360 will inspire us to better understand and protect wolverines and wild places.

Name: Topi Antelope Display their Unique Mating Behaviors
Overview:
Topi antelopes begin to show their mating behavior with specialized snorting and chasing.  Topis are natives of African savannas. They live in small herds. Both males and females have horns so you have to look carefully to sex them.

It is the beginning of breeding season and the males are starting their displays using a high-stepping, specialized prancing, a "rocking canter," that is unique to this species.  The chasing and displaying will get more intense as the breeding season progresses with males establishing small, temporary territories into which they shepherd as many females as they can.  But for now, the males are just practicing and with the increasing heat of the afternoon, most of the herd switches to resting.

Name: A Crocodile Fish Hides in Plain Sight
Overview:
A crocodile fish, or crazy fish, hides in plain sight on the edge of a small coral reef in the Indian Ocean off the coast of Southern Kenya — see if you can find it before it moves.

The crocodile fish is a small predator that specializes in making itself virtually invisible, hiding on the bottom of the ocean and waiting to ambush unsuspecting prey, primarily small fish. To a limited extent, they can also darken or lighten their body coloration, and can align themselves in horizontal, vertical, or even upside-down positions.

Name: Parasites Removed from Barracuda
Overview:
A large great barracuda comes to a cleaning station to have its external parasites removed and injuries “doctored” by thumb-sized bluestreak cleaner wrasses.

Cleaner wrasses concentrate at isolated coral heads that become cleaning stations for large and small fishes alike.  The small blue and black wrasses swim around the barracuda, at times entering the gills and even the open mouth of the big fish.  The cleaner fish bumps the barracuda’s lower jaw to stimulate it to open its mouth allowing the cleaner to swim inside and clean around the large jagged teeth.

Name: Wildebeest Migration
Overview:
More than one and a half million wildebeest migrate about 500 miles from the southern Serengeti in Tanzania to Masai Mara in Kenya.

As they make this journey annually, they must grab mouthfuls of grass and keep moving on.  Their migration requires crossing the Mara river, famous for its enormous Nile crocodiles that lie in wait for the crossing gnu.  It has been shown that the ganu's travel allows them to capitalize on local variation in rainfall and find the richest savanna grass to feed on.  How they manage to track the rainfall is still a scientific mystery.

Name: March of the Leafcutters: A Fascinating Look at Ants at Work in the Forest
Overview: Leafcutter ants are unique in several ways. One of the most notable is their use of leaves as a food source. These ants cut pieces of leaves from plants and then use them to cultivate a fungus, which they then consume as food. The ants are also unique in their highly organized and complex social structures. They have a division of labor among the colony members, with different ants specializing in tasks such as foraging, nest maintenance, and caring for the fungus gardens. Additionally, leafcutter ants have a unique system of communication and are able to use chemical signals to communicate with each other, to find food, and to defend their colony.

Name: Take a Safari Ride Through the Masai Mara of Kenya
Overview: Embark on a journey through the heart of Kenya's wild with a safari ride through the Masai Mara Reserve. See the Big Five and other wildlife in their natural habitats, from majestic lions and elephants to colorful birds and graceful gazelles. Get ready for an unforgettable adventure in the beautiful landscape of the Masai Mara.

Name: Experience the Beauty of South Africa on a Safari Ride
Overview: Join us on an exciting safari ride through a South African wildlife reserve, where you'll see a variety of exotic animals in their natural habitats. From majestic elephants and lions to graceful giraffes and zebras, this tour offers a once-in-a-lifetime experience to witness the beauty of Africa's wildlife. Get ready for an unforgettable adventure!

Name: Drone Flyover of River in the Amazon
Overview: Get a bird's eye view of the beautiful Amazon River with this stunning drone footage. Watch as we fly over the water and catch a glimpse of the rare pink river dolphins swimming below. The Amazon river is home to many unique species, and the pink river dolphin is one of the most fascinating.

Name: Nature's Army: The Incredible Migrations of Army Ants
Overview:
A colony of army ants moves across the rainforest ground in Equatorial Guinea.

Army ants, also known as "swarming ants," are a type of highly social ant species known for their nomadic behavior. 

Army ants are known for their distinctive trail formations, with workers forging ahead to clear a path for the rest of the colony to follow. This behavior allows them to efficiently forage for food over large areas, but also requires a high level of cooperation and communication among colony members.

Name: Cuttlefish Changes Color to Defend Against an Intruder
Overview:
A cuttlefish off the coast of Kenya defends its territory from a potential intruder.

Cuttlefish change color for various reasons such as camouflage, communication, thermoregulation, expressing mood, and deception. The ability to change color is due to the presence of special pigment cells called chromatophores which are controlled by the cuttlefish's nervous system. This enables the cuttlefish to blend in with its surroundings and avoid predators, signal its mating status or assert dominance, regulate its body temperature, express its moods, and deceive its prey by mimicking the appearance of its surroundings.

Name: The Amazing Migration of Fiddler Crabs on Florida's Beaches
Overview:
Fiddler crabs swarm a beach in south Florida, near the everglades.

Fiddler crabs (Uca species) are known for their distinctive large claws, which they use for foraging, courtship, and territorial displays. In the Everglades, fiddler crabs are found in the salt marshes and mangrove swamps that border Florida Bay and the Gulf of Mexico.

Unlike many other species of crabs, fiddler crabs are semi-terrestrial and can tolerate fluctuating salinity levels in their habitat. They are also known to undergo seasonal migrations, moving inland during the dry season to avoid desiccation and saltwater intrusion.

Name: Inside a Honeybee Hive
Overview: Honeybees are essential for the pollination of many flowers and crops. Their hives are important for the production of honey and beeswax, both of which are used in a variety of products.

Name: Octopus Investigates Its Surroundings
Overview:
An octopus investigates a camera on a coral reef off the coast of Kenya.

Octopuses are highly intelligent creatures. They possess complex nervous systems and are capable of advanced problem-solving, learning, and memory retention. Octopuses have been observed using tools, escaping from enclosures, and exhibiting remarkable adaptive camouflage abilities.

Their intelligence is thought to be decentralized, with each arm possessing its own degree of autonomy. This decentralization allows them to continue to perform tasks even if part of their body is injured. They are considered to be among the most intelligent invertebrates and their cognitive abilities are believed to be on par with those of some mammals and birds.

Name: The Surprising Agility of Rhinoceros Beetles: A Tree Climbing Adventure
Overview:
A rhinoceros beetle climbs a tree in a Costa Rican rainforest.

Rhinoceros Beetles (also known as "Oros") are found in the tropical forests of Central America, including Costa Rica. These beetles are known for their unique horn-like appendages on the males' heads and can climb trees. They use these horns to fight for mates, display dominance and to defend themselves from predators.

These beetles play an important role in the ecosystem as decomposers and pollinators and are a popular pet in some countries.

Name: A 360 Journey Through the Majestic Realm of North Pacific Jellyfish
Overview:
A Lion's mane jellyfish floats through the North Pacific Ocean near Alaska.

Lion's mane jellyfish is a species of jellyfish that is named after its striking appearance, which resembles the mane of a lion. It is known to be the largest jellyfish species, with a bell that can reach up to 2.5 meters (about 8 feet) in diameter and tentacles that can extend up to 36.5 meters (nearly 120 feet) in length.

Lion's mane jellyfish contain thousands of stinging cells called nematocysts that they use for defense and to capture their prey. These stinging cells can cause a painful and sometimes dangerous reaction in humans who encounter them, making it important to handle these jellyfish with caution.

Name: Hermit Crabs Take Over Beach
Overview: Hermit crabs are important to an ecosystem as they help to break down organic matter and recycle nutrients back into the soil. They also provide food for other animals, such as birds, fish, and other crustaceans. Hermit crabs also help to aerate the sand on beaches, which helps to keep the beach clean and healthy. Lastly, their shells provide a home for other animals, such as anemones and algae.

Name: Fornicating Frogs: The Incredible Milk Frog Breeding Ritual Caught on Camera
Overview:
Milk frogs breed and croak in a pond in a Costa Rican rainforest.

They are known for their loud and distinctive mating calls, which can be heard during the rainy season when they are most active. Male milk frogs call to attract females and establish territory. These calls are loud and can be heard over long distances, making it easier for females to locate suitable mates.

Name: Painted Dog and Hyena Confrontation
Overview:
A group of painted dogs and a hyena confront each other at a waterhole in the savannah.

Hyenas are mostly scavengers but will drive off and sometimes kill other animals to supplement their diet.

Name: Cheetahs Stalk and Destroy 360 Camera
Overview:
A cheetah family finds and plays with a 360 camera on the African savannah.

Cheetahs are a threatened species, suffering from loss of habitat, illegal poaching, and trafficking.

Name: Silent Serval Moves Through the Bush
Overview:
A serval cat in eastern Africa sneaks up to sniff the camera before sauntering back into the bush. 

Serval cats are unique because of their elongated legs, large ears and slender build. They are also known for their strong hunting skills and agility, as well as their distinctive vocalizations. Their ability to jump up to 4 meters (13.1 feet) horizontally and 2.7 meters (9 feet) vertically makes them skilled hunters in their natural habitat.

Name: Experience the Incredible Lek Mating Ritual of the Greater Prairie Chicken
Overview:
A greater prairie chicken dances and sounds off during its courtship ritual for mates.

Prairie chickens, also known as prairie grouse, perform a courtship dance in the spring to attract a mate. The dance involves a variety of behaviors, including inflating air sacs on the neck, displaying colorful feathers, and making distinctive calls.

The male prairie chicken will perform these displays in an area called a "lek," which is a traditional mating ground. Female prairie chickens will visit the lek to observe and choose a mate based on the male's dance and display. The dance helps the male prairie chicken advertise his fitness and attractiveness to potential mates.

Name: Loud and Proud: The Cicada's Predator Defense Mechanism
Overview:
A cicada in Madagascar perches on a tree and squirts to ward off predators.

Cicadas are insects known for their loud and distinctive buzzing sound, which can reach up to 120 decibels, equivalent to a rock concert.

They have a unique defense mechanism called "predator satiation," where they emerge in large numbers to overwhelm predators, ensuring enough individuals survive to mate and reproduce. Additionally, cicadas can squirt excess fluid to ward off predators.

Name: Lepidoptera Larva: Madagascar's Fuzzy Black Explorer
Overview:
A caterpillar moves along a branch in the rainforests of Madagascar.

Caterpillars are remarkable for their ability to undergo complete metamorphosis, transforming from a larval stage into an adult butterfly or moth through four distinct stages.

To protect themselves during this vulnerable period, caterpillars employ various defense mechanisms, including camouflage, bright warning colors, mimicry, and even chemical defense by ingesting toxic compounds from their host plants, showcasing their adaptability and resilience in the face of predation.

Name: Madagascar's Majestic Comet Moth Takes Flight!
Overview:
A comet moth perches on a tree in the rainforests of Madagascar.

The comet moth, or moon moth, endemic to the island, is known for its striking appearance and large wingspan of up to 20 centimeters (8 inches), making it one of the largest moths on earth.

These moths possess elongated, moon-like tails on their hindwings, which not only create a visually stunning effect but also serve a functional purpose. The wingtips are believed to disrupt the echolocation of predators, such as bats, providing these moths with a unique defense mechanism against predation.

Name: Stunning Giant Pill Millipedes in Madagascar's Rainforest
Overview:
Giant emerald pill-millipedes scour the rainforest floor in Madagascar in search for food.

These millipedes are a species of giant pill-millipede that is endemic to Madagascar's rainforests. With a length of up to 10 cm, it is one of the largest pill-millipedes in the world. 

Its unique defense mechanism, conglobation, allows it to roll into a tight, armored ball, making it challenging for predators like lemurs to prey on them.

Name: Branch Buddies: Madagascar's Amazing Flatid Hoppers!
Overview:
Flatid planthoppers hang out on a branch in Madagascar.

Flatid planthoppers exhibit impressive mimicry, with their flattened body shape and intricate patterns allowing them to camouflage seamlessly with their surroundings.

Additionally, some species secrete wax from specialized glands, extruding filaments that form a protective barrier around them. This not only helps them evade predators by masking their appearance but also acts as a deterrent to certain parasitic insects.

Name: A Giant Madagascar Land Snail Moves Through the Forest
Overview:
A giant land snail in Madagascar moves along a tree trunk.

Madagascar's giant land snail species, belonging to the genus Achatina, are endemic to the island. These giant snails are among the world's largest, with some species reaching lengths exceeding 25 cm (10 inches) and weighing up to 900 grams (2 pounds).

Name: Madagascar's Orb Weaver Wonder
Overview:
A golden orb-weaver spider builds its intricate web in Madagascar.

Golden orb-weaver spiders are renowned for constructing large, intricate webs up to 6 feet in diameter, which are typically built in open areas to maximize prey capture.

Their silk reflects ultraviolet light, attracting insects drawn to UV light and enhancing the web's effectiveness. The combination of these impressive web structures and unique silk properties makes golden orb-weaver spiders both captivating and scientifically intriguing.

Name: Fire Millipede: The Ultimate Survivor in Madagascar's Forests
Overview:
A giant red fire millipede moves along the forest floor in Madagascar.

This millipede is an herbivorous species which can reach up to 25 cm (10 inches) in length and is easily recognizable by its red color and black markings.

When threatened, it can curl up into a ball and secrete a noxious fluid to deter predators. While not much is known about its social behavior, it plays a crucial role in the ecosystem as a decomposer of dead plant matter.

Name: Wave-dodging Wonders: Crabs in Action, Galapagos Style
Overview:
Sally lightfoot crabs hang on to the rocks as ocean waves crash onto them in the Galapagos.

The Sally Lightfoot crab is a visually striking species known for its vivid red, orange, yellow and blue colors, which serve as camouflage in its rocky, coastal habitat.

Native to the eastern Pacific Ocean, these agile and swift creatures are aptly named for their ability to swiftly navigate rocky surfaces and leap from rock to rock, allowing them to evade predators with remarkable ease.

Name: Marabou Stork's or "Undertaker Bird" Appetite for Guts: Scavenging in the Wild
Overview:
A marabou stork, or "undertaker bird," and other scavengers eat and inspect a dead hare in the Masai Mara.

Marabou storks are large scavenging birds found in Kenya. They are known for their unique appearance with a bald head and a large throat sac. The bare head and neck of these birds are adaptations that prevent soiling of feathers when feeding inside carcasses. These birds face competition for food sources from other scavengers, including eagles and warthogs. Eagles are skilled hunters and will often steal carrion from the storks, while warthogs use their sharp tusks to defend their food.

Marabou storks have adapted by having a strong digestive system that allows them to consume even the most putrid and diseased meat, making them a crucial part of the ecosystem's clean-up crew.

Name: The Grim Meal: Hyenas and Vultures Chomp on a Zebra Carcass
Overview:
Hyenas and vultures compete for a zebra carcass in Kenya.

Spotted hyenas and Ruppell's vultures are both scavengers, feeding on the carcasses of dead animals. Spotted hyenas have powerful jaws that enable them to break through bones and feed on the remains of other predators' kills.

Ruppell's vultures have specialized feeding adaptations, such as backward-pointing spikes on their tongues to help remove meat from bone. They can efficiently consume large carcasses with their sharp beaks and strong neck muscles, tearing apart tough skin and muscle.

Both species play important roles in the ecosystem by helping to control the spread of disease and recycling nutrients back into the environment.

Name: Bat-Eared Foxes Face Off Against Banded Mongooses in Kenya's Mara Triangle
Overview: Bat-eared foxes defend their den from a pack of banded mongooses in the Mara Triangle region of Kenya.Banded mongooses inhabit the savannas of sub-Saharan Africa. As packs forage, they sometimes encounter other animals, including bat-eared foxes with their kits, which can result in confrontations. Bat-eared foxes can be seen defending their den from potential threats.Mongooses primarily feed on insects, small mammals and fruits, but do not prey on larger animals like these foxes. Comparatively, bat-eared foxes have a unique dental structure that allows them to feed almost exclusively on insects, such as termites and beetles.

Name: Hamerkops: The Master Fishers of Masai Mara's Serene Ponds
Overview:
A flock of hamerkops fishes in a pond in Masai Mara, Kenya.

Hamerkops are a unique bird species found in a variety of habitats in sub-Saharan Africa, such as wetlands, marshes and forests, and have a diverse diet of fish, frogs and insects. 

Hamerkops employ a range of hunting techniques. If the water is murky, prey is found by probing their open bills into water or mud. To flush out hidden fish, tadpoles and crustaceans, hamerkops may shuffle one foot at a time on the bottom or suddenly spread their wings. Food caught in the mud is shaken before swallowing to clean it, or taken to clearer water.

Name: A Yellow Anaconda Slithers Through the Backcountry
Overview:
A yellow anaconda slithers across a dusty road in the northern Pantanal region of Brazil. 

The yellow anaconda is known for its distinctive yellow scales and immense size, making it one of the largest snakes in the world. They are non-venomous but have powerful constriction abilities, which they use to capture and kill their prey.

Their ability to adapt to aquatic environments allows this elusive reptile to thrive in the remote wetlands of South America.

Name: Monarch Butterflies by the Millions: Masters of Migration Unleashed!
Overview: Each year, monarch butterflies embark on a remarkable 3,000-mile journey to the Monarch Butterfly Biosphere Reserve in Mexico, a UNESCO World Heritage site. Drawn instinctively to their ancestral wintering grounds, they form enormous clusters so densely packed on pine and oyamel fir trees that the branches sag under their collective weight. This mass migration, vital for their survival, is still a natural mystery as they search for safe places to spend the winter.

Name: Yikes Stripes! Zebras Tussle
Overview:
Zebras play and roughhouse in the Masai Mara region of Kenya.

Plains zebras engage in playful behavior such as chasing each other, nuzzling and kicking up their heels. This type of play helps them develop important motor and social skills. Additionally, zebras engage in mutual grooming using their teeth to remove dirt and parasites, which strengthens their bonds and maintains hygiene. This behavior is an important part of their social interactions and helps to promote the well-being of the herd.

Name: Jabbering Jabiru Storks: A Sight to Behold as they Fish and Socialize
Overview:
Jabiru storks fish and socialize with each other at a pond in the Pantanal region of Brazil.

The jabiru stork is unique and memorable for its impressive size and elegant appearance. These birds, standing up to 1.5 meters (5 feet) tall and boasting a wingspan of up to 3 meters (10 feet), are some of the largest storks in the world. 

The clicking of the jabiru's beak may be a form of communication. They also use their distinctive bills to stir up prey and catch their meals, showcasing these remarkable techniques for survival. Their diet primarily consists of fish, amphibians and crustaceans.

Name: Fishing in Harmony: Watch Waterbirds at Work in Brazil's Pantanal
Overview:
Waterbirds fish in a pond in the Pantanal region of Brazil.

The wetlands of Brazil are home to a diverse range of bird species with unique behaviors and fishing techniques. Cattle and snowy egrets hunt cooperatively, using the movements of other birds and animals in the water to flush out their prey. Great egrets and cocoi herons wait patiently to strike at the right moment. 

Roseate spoonbills and jabiru storks actively forage by probing the muck with their bills to detect aquatic animals. Once their prey is located, they close their beaks instantly to swallow it.

Name: World's Largest Rodent in its Natural Habitat: Capybara Foraging in Brazil's Pantanal
Overview:
A herd of capybara, sometimes called "water pigs," forages in Brazil's Pantanal wetland.

The capybara is the largest rodent in the world and native to South America. They inhabit dense vegetation near bodies of water and feed on grasses and other aquatic plants. 

Capybaras are social animals and can often be found in groups of 10-20 individuals. They are considered a keystone species in the Pantanal and play a vital role as seed dispersers and bulk grazers to help maintain the balance of the ecosystem.

Name: Andean Bears  - Watch Them Squeal and Squabble Over Food!
Overview:
Andean bears feast on treats and squabble over food.

Andean bears are also known as spectacled bears due to the distinctive white or light fur markings around their eyes which can resemble eyeglasses or spectacles.

They exhibit both cooperative and competitive feeding behaviors in the wild and use a variety of vocalizations to communicate with one another. These sounds include huffs, snorts and even a unique humming sound. These vocal behaviors play a crucial role in establishing social bonds, expressing emotions and signaling territorial or defensive intentions within their complex social dynamics.

Name: Jaguar in its Natural Habitat: Watch it Prowl Along a River in the Pantanal
Overview:
A jaguar prowls along a riverbank in the Pantanal region of Brazil.

Jaguars are the largest felines native to the Americas and are known as skillful hunters. They live in a variety of habitats in Brazil, including forests, grasslands and wetlands. These semi-aquatic cats use their powerful legs and sharp claws to ambush prey, including caimans, capybaras and deer.

Jaguars are the top predator in the Pantanal and play a crucial role in maintaining a balanced ecosystem. With the highest density of jaguars in the world, this region is an important refuge for these animals, offering a unique opportunity for conservation and research.

Name: Surrounded by Baby Elephants in the Water
Overview: African elephants rush into the water for a quick drink. As the baby elephants wade by, one of the adults pushes the baby and slaps another mother with her trunk, causing the camera to get knocked over and muddied.

Name: Ostrich Stampedes Like a Dinosaur
Overview: An ostrich stampedes past the camera. Dinosaur might have run like this millions of years ago. This is not surprising since birds evolved directly from dinosaurs and managed to survive the great extinction of the dinosaurs 65 million years ago.

Name: Cape Buffalo Gets Spooked
Overview:
A bachelor herd of cape buffaloes makes way for an interloping dagga boy. 

Among Cape buffaloes, two types of bachelor herds generally exist. The first is comprised of males aged four to seven years and the second consists of males 12 years or older. During the breeding season, younger bulls will rejoin a larger herd to mate. Dagga boys which tend to be very old males who are no longer competitive, are isolated animals and therefore adopt an extremely aggressive stance toward threats and are considered quite dangerous.

Name: Coyote Carries an Ermine Weasel in its Jaws
Overview:
A coyote travels along a riverbank in Yellowstone National Park, carrying an ermine in its jaws.

While coyotes are primarily hunters and mainly consume meat, they are omnivorous. During the spring, coyotes will eat grasses and fruit when they are available. Hunted prey typically includes small mammals, insects, birds, fish, reptiles and occasionally larger mammals such as deer.

Name: African Scops-owl Roosts During the Day
Overview: An African scops-owl roosts in a tree and then flies away. The African scops owl is not as territorial as the Eurasian scops owl and will nest in loose aggregations, with the nest sites relatively close to each other.

Name: Surrounded by Swarming Butterflies
Overview: Butterflies swarm around a waterhole. Male African clouded yellow butterflies cluster around drying water holes to sop up salts and minerals that concentrate as the water evaporates. The minerals, which are passed to females when the butterflies copulate, improve the viability of the eggs. In addition to this, a swarm of yellow, a foxy emperor, with its active proboscis sits quietly right in front. A brown veined white butterfly sits slightly to its left, and bright orange spotted jokers come and go from the beach.

Name: Namibian Water Break for Springbok
Overview:
A herd of springbok feed and drink at a pond's edge until a big male greater kudu lumbers through the area.

The size comparison shows how small the springbok are. They can spring vertically more than twice their height, up to two meters, into the air. They are such jumpers a special verb, "pronking," was coined to describe that behavior.

Name: Giraffe Walk-Over
Overview:
An undercarriage view of a giraffe. 

A giraffe has only two gaits: walking and galloping. The animal relies on the forward and backward motions of its head and neck to maintain balance and counter momentum while galloping. Giraffes and a few other animals such as brown bear and camel move both legs on one side and then both legs on the other side. In some cases, the hind leg starts first so there is a slight lag. This is known as "spacing."

Name: Guineafowl Butterfly: Close-Up of its Wings
Overview:
A guineafowl butterfly flies low over the ground, picking up nectar from fallen flowers.

The guineafowl butterfly gets its name from resembling the plumage of the helmeted guineafowl bird. The insect's habitat ranges across much of Africa and even Madagascar. They are often found scattered among bushes and trees in dry, rocky grassland, but can also be found dispersed among abandoned farmland.

Name: Great Curassow Feeds its Lifetime Partner in Costa Rica
Overview:
A male great curassow cares for its lifetime mate by feeding it bits of fruit.

Scientists call this behavior pair bonding, a way to ensure reproductive success.

This video was collected in collaboration with Osa Conservation, a nonprofit organization dedicated to protecting the globally significant biodiversity of the Osa Peninsula, Costa Rica.

Name: Up Close with a Black-footed Ferret
Overview:
An up-close encounter with a black-footed ferret as it comes out of its burrow and scurries away.
This Fort Belknap black-footed ferret was marked with temporary hair dye because it was vaccinated against sylvatic plague and canine distemper. This lets biologists know that the individual has already been caught and they don't need to catch it again.

Special thanks to WWF US and Fort Belknap Tribal Council, along with the Fort Belknap Fish and Wildlife Department.

Name: A Giant Millipede - Large Enough to Count its Legs
Overview: A close encounter with a giant African millipede, the world's largest species of millipede, in South Africa.

Name: Fearless Coyote Eats and then Marks 360 Camera
Overview:
A coyote pauses along a roadside in Yellowstone National Park to mark its territory.

Coyotes are less territorial than other canine species such as wolves and will usually not confront intruders unless a pregnant female is present. Additionally, even when confrontations do happen, coyotes will usually not kill intruders, but rather chase and bite them to drive them away.

Name: March of the Magellanic Penguins
Overview: Magellanic penguins scramble by the camera in the Falkland Islands. On land, Magellanic penguins normally walk upright like humans, but they can go down on all fours for speed, making them unique among birds. The vocalizations heard are believed to facilitate mate recognition and pair bonding.

Name: A Cryptic Puff Adder Meanders Across the Sand
Overview: The puff adder's venom is extremely toxic. The venom immobilizes the small prey on which the adder feeds. The snake can then use its highly temperature-sensitive tongue to follow the warmth of its victim and make the kill.

Name: Chimp Knocks Over Camera and Quiets Spectators
Overview: A habituated chimp claims the right of way on a trail in Uganda while humans cautiously stand aside.

Name: Kudu (Antelope) Running and Jumping
Overview:
Adolescent greater kudu run through the bush in South Africa.

Adolescents have a single twist on their horns while adults have two to three twists. Unlike the antlers of deer species of northern latitudes, which drop their antlers and grow new ones each year, antelope keep their horns for life.

Name: Almost Killed by a Hippo
Overview: A large hippo charges out of the water towards a human, who astonishingly survives by raising his voice and hands to counter-threaten.

Name: Wildebeest Stampede
Overview:
A herd of blue wildebeest in South Africa gets spooked and stampedes across the plain.

Their tight formation and sharp turns confuse predators and complicate take-downs.

Name: Blesbok Water Break
Overview:
A small group of blesbok drink from a pond, before being interrupted by a nearby ostrich.

Blesbok, named for the white blaze on their face, were once great migrators like the famous wildebeest of the Serengeti in East Africa. They migrated annually fom east to west across the plains of Africa in huge herds along with wildebeest, springbok, and zebras.

Name: Close Encounter with a Venomous Prairie Rattlesnake
Overview: A prairie rattlesnake cautiously emerges from its den and sniffs the camera with its tongue before slithering away.

Name: A Common Grey Duiker's Day Out
Overview:
A group of grey duiker forage for food on the outskirts of a settlement in South Africa's bushveld.

Grey duikers are found throughout sub-Saharan Africa. They derive their common name from the Afrikaans word "duik" meaning "to dive," which they frequently do in thick vegetation to escape predators. Duiker are very tolerant of human dwellings and have a diverse diet. While they are mostly herbivorous browsers eating leaves, flowers, fruits and roots, they have also been known to consume insects, frogs, small birds, mammals and carrion.

Name: Spotted Hyena Investigates Camera
Overview: Curious and adaptable, spotted hyenas live in advanced, female-dominated clans. That is, males can be clan members, but only as "second class citizens." Hyenas' razor-sharp teeth and exceptionally strong bites (twice as powerful as lions) allow them to eat the bones of old kills when fresh prey is scarce. By cleaning up old kills, hyenas contribute to African ecosystems. They are also efficient hunters, predating primarily on antelope. Female hyenas have a pseudo-penis, which makes identifying females from males difficult. Clan members get information about another's identity and recent whereabouts by sniffing each other's genitalia.

Name: Rare African Hoopoe Waddles Close-Up
Overview: African hoopoes are known for their colorful crown of feathers and are split into three distinct species that spread across several continents. This species of bird currently has an estimated 5-10 million individuals left, but that number is steadily decreasing due to habitat destruction. Regarded throughout history by many cultures as a sacred sign of virtue or harbingers of war, they adorned the walls of many ancient Egyptian civilizations.

Name: A Curious Cape Buffalo Approaches
Overview: An approaching Cape buffalo can be dangerous. In this case, the young male sniffs out the situation and moves on. Buffalo must deal with being a favored prey of prides of lions. They are extremely tough and short-tempered as their survival against lions can depend on a quick aggressive response - "no questions asked." Their eyesight is poor - if people accidentally get in their path, the consequences can be grave - it's always best to give them a wide berth.

Name: Lions Passing By
Overview: A pride of lions walks by.

Name: Canada Goose Family with Newborn Chicks Waddle by
Overview: A Canada goose family honks and waddles by its nest towards a lake. Most people call this goose a "Canadian goose." However, its scientific name is Canada goose.

Name: Chimp Throws Rock at Cameraman
Overview: A chimpanzee from the Ol Pejeta Conservancy throws a rock at a cameraman and a few guests. "Sweetwaters," the name of the chimp sanctuary, was co-founded by Ol Pejeta, The Jane Goodall Institue and Kenya Wildlife Service.

Name: A Red-eared Slider Turtle Slides through the Wild
Overview: A red-eared slider turtle, or red-eared terrapin, makes its way along the forest floor and into the water. These reptiles get their name from the bright red and orange markings along the sides of their head. They are the most invasive turtle species, as they are also the most popular pet turtle in the United States and around the world. Because of this, they are also the most commonly traded species of turtle in the world.

Name: A Wildebeest Breakfast from a Unique Angle
Overview: Golden and blue wildebeests eat out of a food trough on a farm in South Africa. The Golden Wildebeest is a rare variation in color from the blue wildebeest that naturally occurred along the Limpopo River basin in South Africa, adjacent to Botswana. The first golden wildebeest bull was captured in the early 1990s. Since then, game breeders have selectively bred the color form, ultimately producing pure captive herds of them.

Name: Whacked by an Elephant Head-butt
Overview: An African elephant careens down a steep hill, and knocks over the 360 camera.

Name: Licked by a Lizard
Overview: A monitor lizard wakes up under a solar panel and checks out its environment. The lizard is using the heat from the solar panel to warm up during the South African winter.

Name: Male Sea Lion Threatens an Intruder
Overview:
A male southern seal lion in the Falkland Islands (Islas Malvinas) threatens an intruder, settles down and then threatens again. 

Like most sea lions, the oversized males defend prime beach sites against other males and aggressively herd females that come ashore to give birth, to keep them in their territories until they are once again ready to breed. The Falkland's sea lion population was decimated by commercial hunters. Down to to 4% of historical numbers, it has never recovered though hunting was stopped in the 1950s. One possible reason is warming local seawater temperatures, due to climate change, which may be reducing food availability and the ability of females to properly feed their nursing pups.

Name: Face to Face with a Bull Elephant
Overview:
A bull elephant approaches and looms over a 360 GoPro camera.

Bull elephants can be more than ten feet tall. Their trunks contain more than 40,000 muscles, allowing them to lift more than 700 pounds. Elephants use their trunks not only to reach food but also to sniff and touch it. Their unparalleled sense of smell is four times as sensitive as a bloodhound's.

Name: Giraffes Stick Their Necks Out
Overview: A giraffe moves in close to a camera at a protected reserve in South Africa.

Name: Majestic Impala Pause for Water
Overview:
Impala drink at a man-made waterhole in Dinokeng reserve.

The impala is found in the bushveld and sometimes on the interface between woodlands and savannahs. It inhabits places close to water. Landowners in drier parts of Africa often provide water sources for wildlife. This allows species to survive in areas that have long dry seasons and few permanent water sources such as this one in southern Africa.

Name: Giraffes on a Rampage - A Thunder of Hooves
Overview: A tower of giraffes prompts a jackal to move out of the way.

Name: Giant Plated Lizards Find a Meal in South Africa
Overview: Two wild giant plated lizards explore and find food in the highveld bush of South Africa.

Name: Toxic Fire Salamanders Meander through the Forest
Overview:
A pair of vibrant and toxic fire salamanders walks through the wet brush in the forest.

The fire salamander gets its name from its vivid yellow and black markings, which act to highlight the animal's toxicity. These colored areas coincide with their toxic glands, which produce a substance called samandarin. This toxin causes muscle convulsions, hypertension and hyperventilation in all vertebrates and is thought to help prevent predation.

Name: Caracaras Team up to Keep Vultures at Bay
Overview:
A grouping of striated caracaras eat a piece of carrion‚ a young penguin that had died before they found it. Striated caracaras live on islands in southern South America, primarily the Falkland (Malvinas) Islands. The gregarious and opportunistic feeders keep a turkey vulture from participating in the feast.

Two of the caracaras have yellow bands on their legs. The numbered bands help scientists learn how the birds survive in the Falklands. The caracara population is much reduced compared to historical numbers for reasons unknown - scientists hope to learn why.

Name: Animals of the African Bush - Dwarf Mongoose and Crested Francolin
Overview: A pair of dwarf mongooses and crested francolins investigates a hideaway among some rocks and brush.

Name: Black Bear Encounter in the Wild - Episode 3
Overview:
A black bear ambles by an algae-covered pond in a forest of ponderosa pines.

Black bears use sounds, body language and scent-marking to communicate. Examples of expressive sounds include grunts and tongue clicks used by mothers and motor-like purring used by cubs.

Name: Meerkat Massage Parlor is a Busy Place
Overview: A habituated group of meerkats (called a gang or mob) use a sunny farm yard stoop for a grooming session. Scientists think meerkats use this grooming time to reinforce their social status in the group and to appease more dominant individuals, particularly the dominant female, who's known as the queen. One member of the gang will always serve as a lookout to watch for danger.

Name: Elephant Standoff - Half-Tusk Backs Down
Overview: Bulls shadow female herds and jockey for position to access females in estrus. A female in estrus is receptive to a bull for only one day so being in the right place at the right time is critical. Fights between bulls rarely become violent as in this standoff - but when they do, it can result in broken tusks and seriously injured elephants.

Name: Warthogs Keep a Low Profile for Safety
Overview:
Warthogs forage for food on their knees in the bush in South Africa.

Eating like this allows them to locate and root out food with their sensitive noses while still keeping a close watch on their surroundings. To protect their knees against the thorny African bush, they develop thick callouses as knee pads.

While small, and seemingly defenseless against predators, the warthog's quick response to danger, and razor-sharp tusks, make them formidable prey.

Name: Blue Morpho Butterfly Feeds
Overview:
A blue morpho butterfly flies in and lands to feed on a rotting Gepina fruit.

As it lands and closes its wings, its color instantly changes from brilliant blue to cryptic brown with "menacing" eye-like markings.

Scientists think butterflies use mimicry to confuse birds that would eat them. The blue morpho uses a jerky and unpredictible flight pattern to avoid predation.

Name: Warthog Home Invasion
Overview:
A warthog enters its den backwards.

Warthogs do not create their own dens. Typically, dens are dug by ardvarks and then abandoned, leaving them available for other animals.

Name: Seeing Pink Elephants
Overview: African elephants dust off after a bath and realize that they are being spied on by an unwanted visitor. They decide to make adjustments so that the intruder is forced to see pink elephants.

Name: Curiosity Scared the Cats
Overview: A pride of lions approaches a camera for a closeup and sniff before running away.

Name: Saddlebill Stork and Sacred Ibis in Freshwater Wetlands, Kenya
Overview: A saddlebill stork and African sacred ibis stealthily forage for fish, frogs and other prey in the freshwater wetlands of Maasai Mara, Kenya. The saddlebill easily stands out from other wading birds with a height up to five feet, a wingspan of nearly nine fee,  colorful banded beak and pink-knobbed knees. Hunting alongside it are smaller sacred ibis, white-feathered birds, referred to and worshipped as "Thoth" by the ancient Egyptians.

Name: Greater Prairie Chicken Courtship Ritual
Overview: A greater prairie chicken performs a ritual for mating on a lek in North America.

Name: Eaten by a Spotted Hyena in Kenya
Overview: A 360 camera is stolen by a spotted hyena in Kenya.

Name: Rock Python Slithers Out of its Hole
Overview: A rock python slithers out of its hole to catch some of the sun's warm rays in South Africa. African rock pythons make their homes in abandoned animal burrows. Like all pythons, this one is non-venomous and kills its prey by constriction. After gripping its prey, the snake coils around it, tightening its coils every time the victim breathes out. Death is thought to be caused by cardiac arrest rather than by asphyxiation or crushing.

Name: A Mixed Group of Baboons and Impalas Marches By
Overview: Baboons and impala often travel together, even though they eat different types of food. It is thought that each benefits from the other's watching for potential predators. Both species are favored prey of leopards and both are quick to give warning calls if they detect danger.

Name: Giraffe Running Past Camera
Overview: Giraffes run across a protected reserve is South Africa.

Name: Rescued Baby Orangutans are Given a Second Chance
Overview: Orangutans are very intelligent animals -- having the ability to use tools, for example. These baby Sumatran Orangutans are orphans that were rescued and brought to a rehabilitation center. Once old enough, they will be released into the wild in national parks where they are protected from poachers. For now, every afternoon they are taken to the forest where they can play and practice their climbing skills.

Name: Raided Turtle Nest Gets a Cleanup by Black Vultures
Overview:
Black vultures feeding at this nest are helping the turtle. The black vulture is a scavenger and feeds almost exclusively on carrion. They use their sharp eyes to locate food and regularly patrol beaches for dead animals washed up on shore. Where turtles are nesting, they are quick to locate nests that have been disturbed by predators. The birds are not known to harm intact nests. Cleaning up destroyed nests may help reduce infestations of fly maggots that destroy healthy intact nests.

This video was collected in collaboration with Osa Conservation, a nonprofit organization dedicated to protecting the globally significant biodiversity of the Osa Peninsula, Costa Rica.

Name: Elephants Parade By
Overview: A parade of African elephants crosses a dam and notices an observer. The mischievous juveniles reach out with their trunks to see if they can touch the observer without falling off the dike.

Name: Cape Ground Squirrels Feed and Survey Surroundings for Predators
Overview: Cape ground squirrels, one of southern Africa's less famous residents, start their morning by grabbing a quick bite adjacent to their system of communal burrows. A lookout surveys the surroundings for predators -- snakes, large hawks and jackals. After he gets spooked by a harmless drongo that flies in, the squirrels re-emerge and begin searching for their morning meal.

Name: The Wariness of Warthogs
Overview: A warthog family is spooked by a camera set up near its den.

Name: Playful Spotted Hyena Pups in Kenya
Overview: Spotted hyena pups get playful and close to the camera and each other in Kenya.

Name: Monkey Food Fight
Overview:
Part of a troop of vervet monkeys ventures into the "back of house" of a tourist facility to harvest fallen fruit. A young male cannot help but flash his bright blue scrotum. This is to help convince the others that he has dominance. 

It is believed to be a means of impressing females to mate with him. Studies have shown that those who shine brightest attract the most females. The color is not a pigment. It is caused by the refraction of light (as with rainbows) by highly organized cells on the outside of the scrotum. The females are using brightness as an indicator of overall genetic quality.

Name: A Day in the Life of a King Penguin
Overview: Nesting and post-nesting king penguins head toward a sheltered beach, though one individual seems uncertain and has to be nudged along. The birds will soon be molting into complete new sets of feathers (the "fuzzy" looking one has already started). For 2-3 weeks they will not be able to go into the water, so they are bathing while they can. Bathing is important for keeping feathers clean and water-resistant.

Name: Kissed and Hoovered by a White Rhino
Overview: A crash of white rhino on the savannah in Kenya

Name: Swim with Sea Turtles at a Hawaiian Cleaning Station
Overview: Green Sea Turtles are cleaned by surgeonfish. In coral reef habitats, green sea turtles have a symbiotic relationship with the reef fish that maintain "cleaning stations." Turtles congregate here to have algae removed from their carapaces, flippers and faces. The fish receive a constantly replenished source of food while the turtles get spiffed up for smoother sailing (with less drag).  These cleaning stations are common in the waters surrounding the Hawaiian Islands where yellow-eyed surgeonfish and some additional species of tangs and wrasses maintain the same "restaurants" for many generations of fish. Source - Ruckdeschel, C. and Shoop, 2006. "Sea Turtles of the Atlantic and Gulf Coasts of the United States.

Name: A Troop of Chacma Baboons March Through the Mud
Overview: A troop of chacma baboons with babies march through the mud and perform tricks, reminiscent of gymnastics, at a waterhole alongside impala and greater kudu.

Name: Face to Face with an American Badger
Overview:
An American Badger emerges from its hole.

With short and powerful legs, American badgers are identifiable by their huge fore-claws (measuring up to 5 cm in length) and distinctive head markings.

Filmed at the Charles M Russel National Wildlife Refuge / UL Bend

Name: Black Bear Encounter in the Wild - Episode 1
Overview:
A black bear enters a clearing and pauses to smell its surroundings before taking notice of a nearby tree. The bear proceeds to use the tree as a scratching post.

Black bears are not territorial and remain mostly solitary. The home ranges of both males and females may overlap with ranges being larger where food is scarce and smaller where food is plentiful. In Canada and the United States, home ranges of black bears extend from about 15 to 75 square miles for males. They are considerably smaller for females.

Name: King Cormorants and Rockhopper Penguins Nesting in the Falkland Islands
Overview: King cormorants and rockhopper penguins feed their young in mixed nesting colonies in the Falkland Islands.

Name: Thermoregulating Ostrich Walks through Watering Hole
Overview:
A common ostrich wanders through a waterhole before pushing away some blesbok to find more food. 

Ostriches have developed the ability to help regulate their body temperatures through direct contact with their environments. In hot and arid climates ostriches are known to wade through shallow water holes, so that their lower legs, feet and toes can help lower their body temperatures.

Name: A Band of Female Coatis Comes by - Noses At Work
Overview:
A band of female coati rummages for food in the forest - their sensitive noses sniffing constantly.

Females will accept a single male into their band only when they are ready to breed and then only for a month or so. The rest of the time, males live and feed alone like the young male at the end of this video.  Coati have bear and raccoon-like paws and walk plantigrade (on the soles of the feet), like humans, raccoons and bears.

This video was collected in collaboration with Osa Conservation, a nonprofit organization dedicated to protecting the globally significant biodiversity of the Osa Peninsula, Costa Rica.

Name: Marked by a Hippo
Overview: A hippopotamus marks its territory along the Mara river in Kenya

Name: An Elephant Gets Too Close for Cheetahs' Comfort
Overview: Three young cheetahs are flushed by a bull elephant in musth. The cheetahs run from the elephant while it navigates a slalom course between two 360-degree cameras.

Name: Scarlet Macaws Grab a Quick Snack
Overview:
Scarlet Macaws swoop in and grab a quick bite of palm nuts before soaring away in the Costa Rican rainforest. Macaws are another species that mates for life and are almost always seen in pairs, even when flying in flocks.

This video was collected in collaboration with Osa Conservation, a nonprofit organization dedicated to protecting the globally significant biodiversity of the Osa Peninsula, Costa Rica.

Name: Majestic Kudu Stands Tall in Namibia
Overview:
A bull kudu towers above other antelope such as sable, gemsbok and waterbuck at a waterhole.

It is easy to tell a male greater kudu by its symmetrical spiraled horns that can grow up to 6-feet, and by the abundant throat mane that runs down from its chin. Despite their size, kudu are still vulnerable to predators while drinking. Their large cupped ears make them very sensitive to sound and notoriously hard to approach.

Name: Monkeys (Vervet) Climb Down Tower
Overview: These vervet monkeys were climbing all over the cell tower used to project wifi and cell signals across the entire reserve.

Name: Asian Elephant Checks if a Female is Ready to Mate
Overview: In the forest, a bull Asian elephant (only bulls have tusks in this species) checks out the reproductive readiness of a female with his trunk. He takes a sample of her urine with his trunk and inserts his trunk into the back of his mouth and exposes the sample to a sensory receptor, known as Jacobson's organ. These highly sensitive cells on the organ detect whether she is in estrus and ready to mate If she were, he would immediately raise his trunk over her back and attempt to mount her. Females show a preference for older, larger bulls.

Name: Gemsbok (Oryx) Claims Their Watering Hole
Overview:
A gemsbok, or South African Oryx, is visiting a waterhole in Namibia. The gemsbok chases away a variety of other animals including ostrich, kudu and evenother gemsbok. Watering holes not only provide a source of hydration for the visiting animals but also serve as grazing locations.

The gemsbok is a species of large antelope recognizable in part by their nearly straight horns. Both sexes of gemsbok have horns, with the female's being slightly longer and more slender, and the male's being shorter and thicker. The species forms mixed-gender herds, unlike other antelope species which form male-dominant harems, and are the National Animal of Namibia.

Name: Thirsty Birds at a Waterhole in Arid Namibia
Overview: These double-banded sandgrouses live in arid lands of southern Africa and fly many miles (sometimes up to 100) to reach water to drink. They bob their heads and then tip them back to swallow lots of water that they then carry to their thirsty nestlings back home. The ring-necked doves, with a black collar, drink normally, as they live locally and can return to the waterhole anytime.

Name: Black-browed Albatross Cares for Chick
Overview:
A black-browed albatross keeps its chick warm in a nest of mud, guano (bird poop) and coastal grasses while preening and feeding it.

Black-browed albatross breed in large colonies on top of the cliffs in the Falkland Islands (Islas Malvinas) an archipelago in the South Atlantic Ocean. Black-browed albatross mate for life and have a potential lifespan of up to 70 years. However, tens of thousands are killed each year by longline fishing vessels, which trail thousands of baited hooks on lines up to 80 miles long. The albatross mistake the bait for their food of choice: squid, krill, and fish eggs floating at or near the ocean's surface. The proper weighting of hooks can mitigate the threat.

Name: Rolling Dung with African Dung Beetles
Overview: Two dung beetles battle and fight for their big ball of dung.

Name: Punched by Elephants
Overview:
Elephants tussle at a waterhole in Zimbabwe.

Elephants drink once every day or two, but when they do, they can consume 50 gallons at a time. Elephants cannot drink water through their trunks, but instead use them to suck up water and empty it into their mouths.

Name: Rockhopper Penguins Hop and Swim through Tidal Pool
Overview: Rockhopper penguins hop and swim through a tidal pool. They hop in and use their wings to propel themselves through the water. Once through, they hop out, dry off and rest before heading off to their nests. Their specialized feathers press together in the water, allowing them to stay dry and swim like torpedos, then re-expand out of the water to trap air for superb insulation on land.

Name: Lion Eats Camera and Camera Survives
Overview: An African lion approaches and begins to chew on the camera.

Name: No Sudden Movements as Lion Pride Gets Close
Overview:
This pride of lions saunters by very close to a safari vehicle in the African Bush. 

According to "The Serengeti Lion: A Study of Predator-Prey Relations, the lion is the most social of all wild felid species, living in groups of related individuals with their offspring. Such a group is called a "pride." The multi-female pride is usually protected by a single male, though in some cases, brothers form coalitions. They protect each other against other males that will try to take over the pride and kill the young that were sired by another male. The females will then come into heat and breed with the new master.

Name: Ploughshare Tortoise - One of the Rarest Tortoises in the World
Overview: The ploughshare tortoise is a critically endangered species of tortoise endemic to Madagascar as it is heavily trafficked for the pet trade. The species has become one of the rarest land tortoises in the world.  Even with constant monitoring, the threat from poachers is intense. A radio tag is placed on its shell so rangers can monitor its location.

Name: Ostrich Running with Babies
Overview: Ostrich chicks and parents run close by the camera.

Name: Elephant Seal Fight
Overview: Young male elephant seals square off threateningly, but then focus on resting and practicing threatening calls instead. Awkward on land, southern elephant seals are excellent swimmers, staying underwater for up to 90 minutes and diving up to 6,000 feet to search for fish and squid. Enormous beach masters that hold prime beach real estate may weigh 6,000 pounds and mate with more than 100 females. Thus, youngsters like these spend their pre-adulthood honing their fighting skills in preparation for the day when they might challenge a dominant male.

Name: Banded Mongoose Standing Guard on Hind Legs
Overview: Banded mongooses emerge from their burrow in an old termite mound to find a strange presence. One individual checks it out while the others run off - returning later to stand guard, sometimes standing on their hind legs. When a banded mongoose stands on its hind legs, it is reminiscent of meerkats (meerkats are mongooses). Banded mongooses are primarily found in savanna and woodland ecosystems, usually close to water.

Name: Elephant Mothers Protect Their Babies
Overview:
A herd of African elephant mothers in Zimbabwe protect their babies by keeping them underfoot.

With baby elephants, as with their human counterparts, babies can ignore proper etiquette. When the elephants start to drink, the smaller youngster butts in between two females to get a drink. The adolescent tries to squeeze in and fails, forced to wait its turn. Since elephants often range far between drinking opportunities, young must fill up when they can. After they drink and linger at a waterhole, the tightly-knit family group moves along.

Name: Rock Climbing Mountain Goats Teter on the Edge
Overview:
Several mountain goats wander rocky hillsides in Colorado, traversing the terrain and resting on rocky outcroppings.

Despite being referred to as mountain goats, they are not goats but are in the same family as antelope, gazelle and cattle. They are found exclusively in North America, primarily in the Rocky and Cascade mountain ranges where they inhabit alpine and sub-alpine environments. They prefer higher altitudes during the summer and range below treeline during the winter months.

Name: Lion Dining Etiquette
Overview:
Young lions provoke a coalition of two male lions devouring a wildebeest kill. The adult male lions use many distinctive growls, barks and roars to prevent their cubs from sharing the feast. The young lions comply for a moment, but then repeatedly sneak back for a quick snack. 

These young lions are the offspring of one or both males -- otherwise, they wouldn't be able to "dine" on the wildebeest.

Name: Mom and Baby Asian Elephant
Overview:
A mother and baby elephant leave a river after drinking to feed on, grasses, and rushes. 

Asian elephants feed on a wide range of vegetation from grasses to leaves, bark and even spiny climbing palms (often known as rattan). Asian elephants are considered endangered. There are only about 50,000 remaining. That's about 10% of the number of African elephants remaining in the wild and the number is declining. According to IUCN, the Asian elephant is primarily threatened by loss of habitat and poaching. As their habitat is lost, interactions with humans (human/elephant conflict) are increasing in frequency and intensity, with fatalities occurring on both sides.

Name: Stampeding Elk Have a Pool Party
Overview: A herd of elk in the Rocky Mountains stampede and splash around a pond by the forest.  Elk are among the most sociable deer species. Some herds can grow to more than 400 individuals.  It is estimated that the Greater Yellowstone Ecosystem population of elk is more than 40,000. Living in larger herds can have many benefits, including prevention of predation from wolves, coyotes, mountain lions and bears.

Name: Dung Beetle vs Dung Beetle - Beetles Fight over Rhino Dung
Overview:
Dung beetles fly into a large pile of fresh rhino dung to find a mate and food to raise their young.

Males separate a chunk, make it into a ball that hopefully attracts a mate, and roll it off (with the female hanging on for the ride). The pair finds a spot to bury its prize once she has laid her eggs in it. Males often fight over dung balls. Two strategies become obvious, to roll their own or to take away another beetle's ball.

Name: Geoffroy's Spider Monkeys Eat Palm Nuts
Overview:
Geoffroy's spider monkeys swing through a fruiting tree on their way to a palm tree to check out an inflorescence of ripening palm nuts. Spider monkeys have a prehensile tail which means they can use it to grip things and even hang from. They rarely stand on a branch, but rather show a preference for hanging from any one of their five appendages.

This video was collected in collaboration with Osa Conservation, a nonprofit organization dedicated to protecting the globally significant biodiversity of the Osa Peninsula, Costa Rica.

Name: Rare Footage of the Nearly Extinct Northern White Rhino
Overview: A female northern white rhino is eating her way close, closer and closer to the camera. She is one of two northern white rhinos remaining in the world. This mother and daughter pair are named Najin and Fatu. These critically endangered animals were rescued from poachers and now live in Kenya at the Ol Pejeta Conservancy, a wildlife sanctuary for the northern white rhino as well as more than 110 endangered black rhinos. The fate of the northern white rhino is uncertain, as Najin and Fatu are unable to produce offspring due to their ages, and the sole remaining male northern white rhino died in 2018. With no offspring to continue the lineage, the sub-species is all but extinct. However, scientists plan to fertilize eggs harvested from these females with sperm from the male to produce northern white rhino embryos that would then be implanted in southern white rhino surrogates.

Name: Greater Sage Grouse Courtship Rituals
Overview: North American Greater Sage Grouse engage in courtship rituals that begin during the night and continue until just after dawn.

Name: Surrounded by Wildebeest in the Great Serengeti Migration
Overview:
Blue wildebeest migrate across the Serengeti and the Maasai Mara. Between January and March, half a million wildebeest are born each year in the Serengeti. In February, the month with the highest calving rate, around 8,000 wildebeest are born each day.

Most of these wildebeest are reaching the northern end of their migration where they will feed in the great Masai Mara before working their way back south through Serengeti National Park. Many will cross the Mara river where they face the dangers of that famous crossing filled with crocodiles.

Name: A Curious Jackal Approaches
Overview: Black-backed jackals are opportunistic foragers. They will eat almost anything they can capture or scavenge, including the kills of lions, leopards and hyenas. It also means they must be cautious whenever approaching situations where carnivores, that are reluctant to share their meals, may be lurking.

Name: Surrounded by Running Rhinos
Overview: White rhinos create mayhem in the South African bush. Something has them charged up for a run, though no source can be seen. Vocalizations include snorts, growls, snores, barks, grunts, squeals, croaks, he-he's, laughs, and general utterances of civil disobedience.

Name: Ostrich Babies
Overview:
A male (black) and female (gray) ostrich walk by the camera with their one-week-old chicks. Several females may lay their eggs in a single nest. 

Filmed on location in the Dinokeng Big 5 Game Reserve.

Name: Rockhopper Penguins Swim and Hop in Tidal Cove
Overview: Rockhopper penguins swim in tidal waters and hop across seaweed-strewn rocks in this cove in the Falkland Islands, located off the southern tip of South America. Each year, from October to April, rockhoppers migrate by the thousands to breed among the rocky cliffs of these remote islands. Swift swimmers in the water, thye use their bellies and flippers to maneuver from water onto land. A layer of fat and waterproof feathers keeps them warm in freezing temperatures. Overfishing reduces their food source and contributes to their population decline.

Name: Scratch, Sniff, and Snooze - Elephants Fully Utilize a Tree
Overview: After swimming, elephants stop at a tree to scratch, sniff, rest, and investigate something they haven't seen before. After the baby elephant scrapes against the tree, an adult uses the tree to lean against it for a break.

Name: Meerkat Mob Shares Maze with Mongoose
Overview: Meerkats (suricates) will often co-exist with yellow mongoose and share maintenance of the warren, adding new tunnels and burrows when necessary. The tunnel system has many entrances and exits shared by both species, presumably to offer greater protection.

Name: Sable Antelope at Waterhole
Overview:
Sable antelope take a quick drink at a waterhole.

Their large swept-back horns may seem more for beauty than function, but their looks can be deceiving. The horns are quite effective in deterring large predators that can be stabbed when attacking from behind. Sable will typically stand and fight rather than run from attackers. Head to head fighting between males to determine access to female herds rarely results in injury.

Name: Augur Buzzard Education with Nature's Educators
Overview: Devin Jaffe of Nature’s Educators talks about augur buzzards. Augur buzzards grow up very quickly. As they age, they begin to look like red-tailed hawks as their tails begin to turn a red color. Throughout Africa, augur buzzards spend a lot of time on the ground as well as in the air. Their long legs and powerful short toes help them catch animals while on the ground.

Name: Black Bear with Cute Cubs in the Wilderness - Episode 4
Overview:
A mother black bear, followed by three cubs, wanders by a stream's edge before continuing into the tall grasses.

Black bears have an exceptional sense of smell. Their large nasal mucosa area is 100 times the size of a human's. Black bears are omnivores and their diet consists mainly of herbs, grasses, insects and fruits but will occasionally be supplemented by fish or other meat. Black bears typically only consume meat when more preferred foods are scarce.

Name: Wild Turkey Take Over
Overview:
A flock of turkeys takes over a local pond in Colorado.

Wild turkeys evolved more than 2 million years ago in North America and have a highly structured pecking order. Dominance is key in their social structure. Many turkey species can become aggressive towards humans, thus, it is recommended to return that aggresion by making loud noises and waving one's arms.

Name: Red Fox: Life at the Den
Overview:
A female red fox leaps from the top of her den while her kits run around.

Red foxes are one of the world's most widely occurring carnivores. They range across North America, Europe, most of Asia and even North Africa. Despite living alongside humans for thousands of years, they have never been commonly domesticated as pets.

Name: Never Get This Close to a White Rhino
Overview:
A mother white rhino and her calf stop by a local waterhole and investigate a 360 GoPro Fusion camera. 
They decide it is best to trot away from the unknown stranger. Later, a white rhino bull drops by for a quick drink and camera inspection. The two adult rhinos have been dehorned to discourage poaching.

Name: Cute Jackal Pups Playing Like Dogs
Overview:
Black-backed jackal pups frolic in front of their den in South Africa.

As they mature, the pups will develop the cautious behavior typical of adult jackals in an environment filled with dangerous competitors.

Name: Zebras Brave River Crossing among Waiting Crocodiles
Overview: A large group of common zebras braves enormous Nile crocodiles to cross the Mara River. Some zebras don't make it.  Black forms on the far side of the river show the crocodiles as they chase the zebras.  Almost reaching safety, a young zebra falls as its mother tries to save it before having to flee for her life as the crocs close in.

Name: Elephant Investigates and Destroys Camera Equipment
Overview: An African savanna elephant leaving a water hole investigates and trashes a motion sensor situated behind a log. Notice the relaxed nature of this elephant as it inspects this new feature on its path. It finds the sensor with its trunk and flings it to the side with minimal effort.

Name: African Penguins on the Rocks
Overview: These African penguins were previously known as "jackass" penguins because the male's mating call, technically known as its "ecstatic display song," sounds much like the braying of a donkey. The African penguins, are found only in southwestern Africa where they nest mostly on small islands. Unfortunately, their numbers have declined drastically in the last 30 years so much so that scientists fear they could become extinct in the next few years.

Name: European Badger Cubs Wrestle Outside Their Den
Overview:
A clan of European badgers is seen playing and wrestling outside its den, or sett, in the Scottish countryside.

European badgers are the most social of badgers. Clans consist of six adults on average. Some clans have been recorded with up to 23 individuals. A sett's entrance is frequently marked by discarded dried straw, leaves and grass, which are used as bedding materials. This discarded matter also doubles as a way to mark the clan's territory.

Name: Warthogs Invade Monkeys
Overview:
Vervet monkeys foraging at a waterhole get interrupted by warthogs.

Warthogs primarily graze on grass and forage for roots, tree bark and berries. They do not prey on other animals, and rarely eat meat.

Name: Black Bear with Cute Cubs in the Wilderness - Episode 1
Overview:
A mother black bear and her three cubs traverse a grassy meadow, stopping briefly to forage.

Black bears have litters every 2 years in good conditions, with 2-3 cubs typical in each litter. The cubs weigh only 1/2 lb to 1 lb at birth but grow quickly given sufficient food supply, and can weigh up to 165 lbs by their first fall. While the birth rate of male and female cubs is nearly 1:1, humans kill far more male bears than females, and, as such, among the mature bear population there is often only one male for every 2-5 females.

Name: Black Bear Encounter in the Wild - Episode 2
Overview:
A black bear pauses at a small pond to examine a nearby tree before moving on.

Black bears are excellent climbers and are often photographed scaling trees. Their claws give them a strong grip and the branches offer adolescent animals safety from predators.

Name: Black Bear with Cute Cubs in the Wilderness - Episode 2
Overview:
A mother black bear and her three cubs travel through a clearing to a small pond at the foot of a hillside.

While often found wandering at a leisurely pace, when necessary, black bears can move at impressive speeds. Lean bears can move at speeds over 30 miles per hour, while heavier bears, which are prepared for hibernation in their winter coats, are slower and tire quickly.

Name: Black Bear Encounter in the Wild - Episode 4
Overview:
An American black bear investigates a mountain pond and its surroundings in Colorado, USA.

These typically solitary mammals are generalists, occupying a variety of habitats ranging throughout Canada and the United States, and are present (though uncommon) in Mexico. American black bears are found in coniferous and deciduous forests, pinyon-juniper woodlands, chaparral and even desert scrub and grasslands. In Mexico, American black bears inhabit plant communities dominated by deciduous and evergreen oaks and montane chaparral. Their diets vary seasonally with food availability. In springtime, grasses and forbs make up the bulk of the American black bear's caloric intake, with berries and insects being preferred during summer. In the fall, the bears feed primarily on acorns and other nuts before hibernation.

Name: Red-tailed Hawk Swoops in and Eats its Prey
Overview:
A red-tailed hawk sinks its talons into its prey before taking a bite with its hook-shaped bill.

The red-tailed hawk is an opportunistic carnivore, and its diet includes more than 500 prey species. Its prey can include rodents, snakes, fish, amphibians, rabbits and even other birds.

Name: All Cats are Cute and Curious - Lion Cub Chews Camera
Overview: A curious lion cub in Zimbabwe plays with,  chews on and tries to swallow a tripod and 360 camera.  The cub does its best to figure out how the camera might be killed and devoured. Does its playfulness remind you of a house cat?

Name: Africa's Smallest Carnivore on the Loose - Dwarf Mongoose
Overview: Members of a family of common dwarf mongooses search for food and drink from a dripping fountain. They are joined briefly by a Smith's bush squirrel with its big bushy tail.

Name: Hissing Mute Swan Tries to Intimidate Others
Overview:
A bevy, or group of mute swans, floats up and down a stream foraging for food and communicating with one another.

Mute swans are some of the more aggressive waterfowl species and often make hissing, grunting and snorting noises, especially when communicating with younger swans, or cygnets. They are highly protective of their territory and offspring and will often hiss when being threatened. If warning calls to not deter intruders, mute swans can attack using tiny bone spurs found in their wings.

Name: Wild Tapir Discovers a Secret Pond
Overview:
A Baird's tapir seeks out the cool refuge of a small pond.

Tapirs feed primarily at night when it is cool and rest in swampy, shaded areas during the day. They are herbivores feeding on fallen fruit, leaves and the soft stems of plants such as heliconia. Their range is restricted primarily to Central America where habitat destruction and hunting have reduced their population by more than 50% in the last 30 years ... making them an endangered species.

Name: An Explosion of Gliding Treefrogs
Overview:
An army of treefrogs competes for mates in a rainforest canopy in Costa Rica. Gliding treefrogs are named because of their large webbed feet allowing them to glide through the air. To reproduce, gliding treefrogs gather in "explosive breeding" concentrations over small temporary ponds that fill seasonally with heavy rainfall. The frogs appear overnight above these ponds and lay their eggs on leaves. When the eggs hatch in six days, the tadpoles fall into the pond below. The adults disappear into the canopy as quickly as they arrived.

This video was collected in collaboration with Osa Conservation, a nonprofit organization dedicated to protecting the globally significant biodiversity of the Osa Peninsula, Costa Rica.

Name: Wild African Animal Stampede
Overview: A wildebeest stampede is followed by many other African safari animals, such as zebra, giraffe, impala, blesbok, rhino, warthog and ostrich.

Name: Giraffes Wander through the Bush
Overview: Giraffes at sunset. With human populations growing fast, human-giraffe conflict is becoming more common and some giraffes are even being hunted beyond what can be replaced by nature.

Name: Lick, Bite, and Roll - Cheetah
Overview: A cheetah, being prepared for release into a national park, licks and bites the camera as it lounges around its water hole. The cheetah is considered vulnerable to extinction because its global population is declining. Thus, numerous efforts are being made to reestablish and fortify existing local populations by releasing individuals from areas where their numbers are stable. Conservationists call this rewilding. It is an important, though expensive tool, that has brought numerous species back from the brink of extinction.

Name: Close Encounter with a Chacma Baboon in South Africa
Overview: A chacma baboon in South Africa gives an up-close and personal look at the camera.

Name: American Kestrel Education with Nature's Educators
Overview: Devin Jaffe talks about American kestrels. American kestrels are one of the few raptors that have distinct male/female color morphs. Males have blue-grey wings, whereas females have a more rufous coloring. Kestrels are the smallest falcon in the United States and are nicknamed the "Sparrow Hawk" for their ability to hunt other birds in addition to ground-based prey.

Name: Barn Owl Education with Nature's Educators
Overview: Devin Jaffe of Nature’s Educators talks about the common barn owl. The common barn owl is important to keeping the ecosystem in balance as their diet consists of mice, rats and other small animals. The flutings on an owl’s feathers break up the air around their wing, which makes for nearly silent while flapping. This makes them effective hunters. They also have zygodactyl toes with two in the front and two in the back, however, they can also move one toe forward for capturing prey.

Name: Giraffe Investigates the Area and Runs Away
Overview:
A giraffe walks down a dirt road in the South African bush.

The giraffe, the world's tallest terrestrial animal, does not have a normal ungulate gait. They walk like camels and run like horses.

Name: Bobcats Scramble Down Tree Near Town in Colorado
Overview:
A pair of bobcats down a tree in the Rocky Mountains of Colorado.
