Bobcats, also known as red lynx, are native to North America and inhabit ecosystems such as woodland areas, semi-arid deserts and urban-forest edges. Due to their wide range, bobcats are at risk of habitat fragmentation and losses in genetic diversity due to human population encroachment across their territories.

Name: Young Elk with Attitude
Overview: Curious members of a herd of Rocky Mountain Elk in Colorado examine the 360 camera in their path. Their noses do the close-up sniffing. It passes their investigation and they move on.

Name: Polar Bear on the Hunt for Food
Overview: A polar bear discovers the aftermath of a seal kill. Polar bears have an extremely sensitive sense of smell and can detect seals from miles away and hidden under snow.

Name: Where the (Cape) Buffalo Roam
Overview: An obstinacy of cape buffalo find a 360 camera and inspect it with their tongues.

Name: The Real Screaming Marmot Sounds Off
Overview:
Yellow-bellied marmots gather alpine vegetation, scurry in the scree, and sun themselves on a Colorado mountainside.

These marmots live in colonial burrows with up to 20 individuals, usually with a single dominant male. While yellow-bellied marmots spend about 80% of their lives in their den, approximately half of that time is spent hibernating. Upon awakening in the spring, males will begin digging a new home, to which they will attract between two and four females to reproduce. Each female may bear a litter consisting of 3-5 pups, but only half will typically survive.

Name: It's Hard to Get a Drink Around Here - Giraffe Try to Drink
Overview:
Giraffes drink from a waterhole in South Africa.

Giraffes can reach high into trees for food but have more difficulty reaching the ground. A giraffe's large neck veins contain a complex system of valves that stop the blood from flowing backward and pooling when it dips its head to take a drink.

Name: Trampled by a Tower of Giraffes
Overview:
A tower of giraffes walks directly overhead a camera at a muddy waterhole in Kenya.

Giraffes are heavy animals but have unusually skinny limb bones for an animal of their size. To support their weight, giraffes have a special suspensory ligament structure located in their limbs. This ligament is elastic and not muscular, allowing giraffes to support their weight without actively engaging their muscles, thereby reducing fatigue.

Name: Barbary Falcon and Harris's Hawk Education with Nature's Educators
Overview: Devin Jaffe of Nature’s Educators provides a high-level comparison between hawks and falcons to help observers distinguish the differences between the two.

Name: Amazon Pink River Dolphins from a Drone
Overview: Fly over Lake Amana in Brazil with Amazon pink river dolphin. Pink river dolphins are seen singly and in pairs. Amazon pink river dolphin are a species of toothed whales. They are currently classified by IUCN as "Data Deficient", i.e., their numbers are unknown.

Name: Deadly Puff Adder Released into the Wild
Overview: A deadly puff adder snake gets released back into the wild. Venomous snakes are sometimes found around tourist lodges, and rangers must relocate them for the safety of guests.

Name: Forest Elephants Guzzle Mineral Water
Overview:
Forest elephants drink from a bai in the Central African Republic.

The water from these deep pools is rich in nutrients like calcium and phosphorus which aids in strengthening an elephant's bones.

Name: Carried Away by Lions
Overview: Lion cubs and adults grab a 360 GoPro camera and scamper away with it -- providing a perspective of being carried away by a lion.

Name: Lions Nuzzle And Play like Cats
Overview: African lions roll on their backs and nuzzle each other.

Name: Lions in the Wild Get Frisky
Overview:
A male lion approaches a female to mate in the Masai Mara of Kenya.

The male lion's penis has spines that point backward, much like other felines. When it is withdrawn, the spines may cause the female to ovulate, due to the raking of the walls of the female's vagina. After a gestation time of about 110 days, one to four cubs may be born, which typically happens away from the rest of the pride in a secluded area.

Name: Stampeding Bison in Yellowstone
Overview:
American bison jaunt along a snow-packed roadway in Yellowstone National Park. These bison use their massive heads to plow away the snow that covers the grasses they need to survive the winter.

At an estimated 4,800 individuals, the herd in Yellowstone is the largest on public lands. This herd is also the only one in the US that was not fully extirpated and later reintroduced. Today there are an estimated 31,000 American bison globally, found primarily in a few national parks and nature reserves.

Name: Elephants From A Bird's Eye View
Overview: As three female elephants walk down a steep incline - the leader stops to eat. The second elephant pokes the leader iwith her tusks to prod her along. Elephants often use their tusks to not so gently prod other herd members to move out of the way.

Name: Mischievous Macaques Monkey Around with Camera
Overview: Monkeys (crab-eating macaques), like humans, are infinitely curious and love to take things apart. Here, young long-tailed macaques in Indonesia play with and try to dismantle a 360 GoPro camera.

Name: Secretarybird Vomits Snake to Feed Chick
Overview: A Secretarybird regurgitates a snake to feed to its nesting chick.

Name: The Largest Waterfowl Birds in Yellowstone National Park
Overview:
A group of trumpeter swans floats down the Madison River in Yellowstone National Park, before flying away upstream. 

With wingspans up to eight feet, and a weight of almost 25 pounds, these swans are among the largest birds in the world which are still capable of flight. Almost extirpated from the continental United States by 1930 due to overhunting and habitat loss, trumpeter swans once ranged from Alaska to northern Missouri. Through extensive population management, resident swans in Yellowstone provided the breeding stock for a successful recovery later in the century.

Name: Happy Black Rhino Rolls Around in the Mud
Overview:
A black rhinoceros gets a thorough coating of mud at a wallowing site in Kenya. Rhinos wallow for many reasons. This behavior primarily helps keep the animal cool and protects their skin from sun and parasites. 

Like the individual seen here, adult black rhinos are typically solitary animals and only gather to mate. Once a female black rhino becomes pregnant, she will gestate for 15 months. After the calf's birth, it will remain with the mother for a period of up to two years before starting a life of its own.

Name: Swim with Manatees in their Endangered Habitat
Overview: The American manatee is a gentle and intelligent herbivorous marine mammal. During colder months they head to the warm waters of Florida's fresh-water springs to feed and take refuge. Manatee populations are currently threatened by warm-water habitat loss, boat collisions and red tide.

Name: Grevy's Zebra Takes a Dustbath
Overview:
A herd of Grevy's zebra stirs up savannah dust on a hot day.

Dustbathing, characterized by twisting and rolling about on dry earth, is common among many animals and is likely done to remove parasites and flies from hair and skin. Although it's been discovered that zebra stripes help keep flies and other dangerous insects away, dustbathing is another way to protect themselves. Diseases such as equine influenza and sleeping sickness can be transmitted via insect bites, so zebras must maintain a healthy coat.

Name: Monkey Business
Overview: In a troop of vervet monkeys, the male with the bright blue scrotum is boss. The monkeys have found a stash of food, which the youngest ones can eat by laying low, but when the big guy threatens, all challengers flee, chasing each other as they run.

Name: A Rainbow of South African Birds Enjoying a Drink
Overview: Free-standing water is rare in the woodland habitats of southern Africa. A sunny corner of protective vegetation set up with splashing water and snacks of corn attracts a rainbow of local birds to this African bush habitat in the Rainbow Nation.

Name: Hyenas Play at Their Den
Overview:
A young-male spotted hyena steals a 360 GoPro camera and runs off with it. 

Hyenas are often misunderstood as "bloodthirsty villains." Their hunting style is cunning, efficient and relentless. When the clan is at its den, they are curious, gentle and playful.

Name: A Herd of Grevy's Zebra Surround the Camera
Overview:
Grevy's zebra sniff, snort and spook at a waterhole in the Masai Mara, Kenya.

The Grevy's zebra, also known as the imperial zebra, is the most threatened of all zebra species. They are the largest of all wild equines, have larger ears and narrower stripes. Studies show that their stripes serve to protect them from various threats, such as biting insects and other predators. This could be due to the polarizing effect light has when the zebra is stationary, compared to other animal coat patterns. Other studies suggest that stripes produce visual illusions, such as the wagon wheel effect, when in motion, making it harder for flies and insects to land.

Name: How to Survive Being Attacked by a Hippo
Overview:
A hippo charge is nothing to be snorted at. Get a close-up look at a hippo charge and follow a discussion of what went right, and wrong and how to avoid getting into a similar situation.

Hippos kill more people than any other large African animal. Hippos are notoriously aggressive and can charge out of the water at 30km/hr to spar with other hippos, or to defend themselves against potentially threatening humans.

Name: Bird of Paradise Mating Dance
Overview: A male western parotia cleans his court and performs a mating dance for the females. One of New Guinea's spectacular birds of paradise, the parotia male maintains an area on the forest floor clear of leaves and sticks where he dances to attract females for mating. He also shows off his ornaments: neon silver forehead, brilliant blue eyes, flashing iridescence and four long antennae-like feathers to complement his tutu-like plumage.

Name: Prairie Dog Stands Alert for Predators
Overview:
This white-tailed prairie dog stands upright in the search for predators such as black-footed ferrets, golden eagles and badgers.

Predators aren't the only thing that threatens these rodents. Prairie dogs are susceptible to the Sylvatic Plague, which is transmitted by fleas and is a bacterial disease that affects many other mammal species. All four species in the United States are at risk of contracting the disease, with prairie dogs suffering an extremely high mortality rate at or above 90 percent. Many species depend on the prairie dog's survival as it is a keystone species and an indicator of an ecosystem's overall health.

Name: Best of Invertebrates
Overview: More than 97% of  the species on Earth are invertebrates.  Learn about the many unique traits of a few of them.

Name: Black Bear with Cute Cubs in the Wilderness - Episode 3
Overview:
An American black bear sow and her cubs wallow in and forage around a mountain pond.

Female American black bears typically begin breeding around three years old and will continue to do so in an every-other-year cycle. Although the mating season lasts from May to August, these bears will delay embryo implantation to ensure that the young are born during the winter denning period. Litter sizes vary from one to five cubs, with twins or triplets being the most common.

Name: Eaten by a Lion - The Last View Seen by its Prey
Overview: A male lion grabs a camera and carries it away in its mouth.

Name: Long-tailed Macaques
Overview: Long-tailed macaques, a species of monkey, examine and disassemble a tripod. The monkeys eventually carry the camera to a different location, where they tear off the camouflage and examine it in the sunlight.

Name: Black Rhino with Hooked Lip Enjoys a Snack
Overview:
A black rhinoceros uses its "hooked lip" to feed in Kenya.

Black rhinos have a unique prehensile upper lip which allows them to "pluck" the branches and shoots off of small trees and bushes. This means grasses make up 30-40% of the overall diet for black rhinos, compared to the white rhino, which consumes almost 100% grasses.

Name: Lions Use Cameras as Cat Toys
Overview: African lions destroy, chew, and carry away GoPro wildlife cameras.  A lion's mouth is designed for killing and eating. Adult lions have 30 teeth, four of them are canines that can grow up to seven centimeters long. Since they only eat meat, lions don’t really chew their food. They only need to cut meat into smaller sections to swallow. Their teeth are so specialized for cutting meat that they can’t crush the tougher parts of an animal like bone or cartilage. A lion’s tongue is covered in tiny spines, which face backwards, and are used to scrape meat from bones.

Name: An Agouti and a Coati Walk into the Forest
Overview:
An agouti and a coati forage for food in Costa Rica.

Although these species' biological niche spaces may occasionally overlap due to the coati's more generalist nature, agoutis are part of the order Rodentia, whereas coati are classified as order Carnivora. While agoutis primarily consume fallen fruit, leaves and roots, they have occasionally been seen to eat bird eggs as well, a habit they also have in common with the coati. Agoutis are one of the few species that can open Brazil nuts without tools, thanks to their strength and exceptionally sharp teeth.

Name: Forest Elephants Gather at a Famous Mineral Spa
Overview:
Forest elephants, different from savannah elephants, venture into a forest bai filled with mineral pools.

A forest elephant's ears are more rounded, and their tusks tend to be straighter and thinner. Research is showing that forest elephants rarely mate with the more common savanna elephant, leading some scientists to consider them a separate species.

Name: Rock Hyraxes Are Cute But Not Good at Climbing Trees
Overview: Rock hyraxes are the elephant's closest living relative. As proof, they have elephant-like toenails and padded flat-bottomed feet, that are great for climbing on rocks. Climbing tree branches to reach fresh leaves to eat is another story. The young ones practice jumping and hanging on while the patriarch guards the group. He can have as many as 50 offspring to protect from predators.

Name: The Sixth Mass Extinction
Overview: Approximately 100 mammal species have fewer than 1,000 individuals remaining in the wild. Animals around the world are at risk of extinction due to habitat loss, poaching, civil unrest, over-harvesting of the food chain, bushmeat hunting, the pet trade and a multitude of other reasons. Rhinos, cheetahs, lions, giraffes, elephants, penguins and many other species are under severe extinction pressures. Previously abundant populations of animals may soon be headed for "endangered" status. Please join us in our efforts to conserve this planet's remaining biological diversity.

Name: Elephants at a Waterhole Show Tranquil Power
Overview: Powerful giants enjoy the tranquility of a quiet waterhole in Zimbabwe's Hwange National Park. Hot and dry, Hwange supports thousands of elephants, which in dry seasons depend on scattered waterholes for their daily hydration. Many elephants depend on water pumped from bore holes. Despite the seemingly endless turmoil Zimbabwe has endured, park officials, local communities and tourist lodges have kept the water flowing.

Name: Sit Under an African Elephant
Overview: These elephants in South Africa are viewed from a 360 GoPro camera placed at ground level. The elephants step over the camera to provide a unique view from the ground - looking straight up at the pachyderm.

Name: Fox Puppies (Kits) Attack
Overview:
A family of bat-eared foxes interacts on the savannas of eastern and southern Africa.

An adult sits and watches over four young kits. To the left is the entrance to their den. When the kits get close to the mother, she grabs them and grooms them. Bat-eared foxes are fastidious - adults frequently groom each other and their young, a behavior called allogrooming. The kits spend much of their time out of the den running and playing.

Name: World Wildlife Tour - Over 40 Species
Overview: Travel around the world to see more than 40 animal species. Visit Africa, Asia, Central America and Antarctica on a world safari.

Name: Enveloped by Agile Mangabeys
Overview: In a forest in the Central African Republic, a troop of Agile Mangabeys swings by the camera and pauses to investigate. Although generally arboreal, they do spend a significant portion of their time on the ground, especially during the dry season. Group size can be as high as 18 members, led by a single adult male. Group meetings can be friendly and may involve the exchange of members.

Name: Helicopter Safari
Overview: Take a ride with wildlife vets as they perform various objectives to protect animals, including darting, capturing and herding.

Name: Lizard Steals Croc's Eggs
Overview:
A Nile crocodile drops her guard and pays the price.

A Nile crocodile momentarily leaves the nest she has been guarding and a Nile monitor lizard to digs in and steals some of her eggs.  Female Nile crocodiles aggressively guard their eggs, generally leaving only for short stints. Nile monitor lizards feed on everything from carrion to small mammals and birds. Their flicking tongue picks up chemicals from the air and ground that it analyzes in a special organ on the roof of its mouth, allowing it to detect hidden foods such as the buried crocodile eggs.

Name: A Slice of Life at the Swift Fox Den
Overview:
Outside their den, on the shortgrass prairie, a litter of swift fox kits plays and forages while their mother remains alert for threats. 

Each monogamous swift fox pair will produce only one litter each year but may occupy several dens during that time. Dens are typically abandoned due to prey scarcity or the prevalence of skin parasites that accumulate in the burrow. Pups are born during springtime but do not emerge for about a month. They remain with their parents until fall. Social organization is based on female territorial dominance, with males emigrating if females are killed or removed.

Name: Saving Elephants with Honey Bees
Overview: A team of conservationists from Colorado's Butterfly Pavilion travels to Tanzania in Africa to save elephants and protect people. The Bees for Elephants program uses wild African honey bees and their hives, hung on fences in strategic areas, to guard crops and help protect communities. When migrating elephants bump the fences and disturb the hives, the defensive bees sting the elephants and chase them away. Elephants learn what areas to avoid and pass that information on to other members of the herd. Communities and elephants benefit from fewer human-wildlife conflicts. Beekeepers benefit from  the honey the bees produce which is sold at local markets.

Name: The Jaguar Effect - Protecting Our Planet's Beating Heart
Overview:
"The Jaguar Effect" transports viewers to the Pantanal wetland of Brazil, where dedicated researchers work to identify and protect jaguars, a crucial keystone species. 

Learn about the delicate interaction between jaguars, the lush ecosystem and the countless animals that depend on their presence. As the researchers unravel the secrets of these felines, their efforts become a beacon of hope, fostering ecotourism and inspiring a profound appreciation for the jaguars' role in safeguarding the natural balance of the region.

Name: Rare 360 Footage: Two Adult Bare-Faced Curassows with Chicks Foraging in the Pantanal
Overview:
A bare-faced curassow family forages in the Brazilian forest.

Discover the fascinating bare-faced curassow, a large, ground-dwelling bird species found in the Pantanal region of Brazil. They are known for their high pitched whistles and distinctive appearance, with females being more brightly colored than males. 

Breeding happens during the rainy season. Newborn chicks hatch in an advanced state, being able to walk and feed themselves almost immediately. The male helps care for the chicks until they are fully independent.

Name: Discover the Crested Caracara: A Bird with Mood-Reflecting Headgear!
Overview:
Southern crested caracaras near a pond in the Brazilian Pantanal.

The southern crested caracara is easily recognized by its unique crested head, consisting of elongated black feathers that can be raised or lowered, reflecting the bird's mood during social interactions. Additionally, their vibrant facial skin, ranging from yellow to orange or even red, adds to their striking appearance. This bare skin not only contributes to the bird's distinct look but also plays a role in thermoregulation and communication within the species.

Name: Tawny Eagle Food Delivery Service
Overview:
A tawny eagle delivers multiple meals to her juvenile offspring.

The tawny eagle, a large bird of prey found in Kenya and other parts of Africa, primarily hunts small to medium-sized mammals, birds and reptiles. The chicks are initially fed regurgitated food, and are gradually introduced to solid foods by the parents tearing off small pieces of prey.

Tawny eagles are also known to engage in kleptoparasitism, a behavior in which they steal food from other birds.

Name: Giraffe Rodeo : Wranglers Wrap Wiley Giraffes for Wildlife Work
Overview:
Wildlife vets in South Africa work across land and air to dart, capture and relocate southern giraffes.

Veterinarians and their support crews relocate giraffes to new habitats to help maintain healthy populations and increase ecosystem biodiversity.  These teams use a combination of tools and techniques. They use helicopters to pursue and dart, ground teams to rope and tackle, and special transport vehicles to relocate these magnificent animals. It takes several teams and many moving parts to ensure the successful translocation of the giraffes.

As a wildlife veterinarian in South Africa, William Fowlds encounters a diverse range of animal species, including elephants, lions, cheetahs, and giraffes, providing medical care, performing surgeries and rescues, and working tirelessly to protect and conserve these iconic creatures and their habitats.

Name: Bouncing Baboons on a Slippery Slope
Overview: A troop of baboons stops to play on a springy and slippery tent roof while looking for fruit in the trees at a camp in Zimbabwe.

Name: Elephants Go Swimming - Bring Their Trunks
Overview: A herd of African elephants play, swim, and bathe at a waterhole in South Africa.

Name: Impala Stampede and Flyover in Slow-Motion
Overview: A herd of impala in South Africa stampede using powerful leaps and sharp turns, which are often used to escape predators. Impalas are a relatively common antelope and a key prey species for large carnivores from Kenya to South Africa.

Name: ChewCam - Lion Edition
Overview: A lion rides on top of a safari vehicle at the Marakele Animal Sanctuary, which gives tours to guests in a mobile enclosure while the lions are free to interact with them. Despite the flurry of activity seen here, lions spend much of their time resting and are inactive for about 20 hours per day. Although lions can be active at any time, their activity generally peaks after dusk with a period of socializing and grooming. Intermittent bursts of activity continue until dawn when hunting most often takes place.

Name: Sexual Dimorphism in Nyala Up-Close
Overview:
A group of Nyala meandering through the African bushveld.

Nyala are well known for their extreme sexual dimorphism. Sexual dimorphism is the condition where the two sexes of the same species exhibit different characteristics beyond the differences in their sexual organs. The condition occurs in many animals and some plants. Differences may include secondary sex characteristics, such as size, weight, color and markings. It may also include behavioral and cognitive differences. These differences may be subtle or exaggerated.

Name: Grey Wolves Destroy Camera in Yellowstone
Overview:
A grey wolf pack roams its territory in the Greater Yellowstone Ecosystem during a snowy winter.

Grey wolves were documented in the Greater Yellowstone Ecosystem back in 1872 when the national park was originally established. The wolves were hunted and killed due to perceived conflicts with game species and livestock until the 1940's when they were rarely seen. By the middle of the century, wolves were almost completely lost from the lower 48 United states. After the grey wolf was classified as an endangered species in 1974, efforts began the following year to restore a population in Yellowstone. However, it was not until 1995 that 31 wolves were relocated to the park from western Canada.

Name: Arachnid Adventure: Witness the Oklahoma Brown Tarantula Mating March
Overview: Arachnid Adventure: Witness the Oklahoma Brown Tarantula Mating March

Name: Predators on the Prowl: Bears, Wolves, and Jaguars in Their Wild Habitats
Overview:
A range of predator species, including the black bear, grey wolf, lynx, coati, red fox, and jaguar, navigating their natural habitats.

Each species exhibits unique adaptations that allow them to thrive in diverse environments, from North American forests and mountains to the tropical regions of South America. Highlighting these behaviors underscores the importance of habitat protection, particularly for those in rescue centers that provide refuge to these animals when natural habitats are compromised.

Name: Death Roll: Nile Crocodiles Devour Hippo Carcass in Shocking Display of Power
Overview:
Nile crocodiles crawl inside a hippo carcass floating in the Mara River of Kenya.

Crocodiles, known for their death roll, use this move to disorient and tear apart the tough hide of their prey.  In this video, they use this technique to eat a hippo carcass.

In Kenya, the Nile crocodile is known to occasionally prey on hippopotamuses (Hippopotamus amphibius). However, it is relatively rare for crocodiles to successfully take down adult hippos, as they are large and aggressive animals that can defend themselves effectively. More commonly, crocodiles scavenge on dead or weakened hippos that have died from natural causes or other causes.

Name: Rhino Relocation
Overview:
Dr. Will Fowlds, a wildlife vet in the Eastern Cape of South Africa, transports a dozen white rhinos to a protected reserve.

Rhinos are often relocated for conservation purposes including the establishment of new populations and to prevent inbreeding. This process can be dangerous for both the rhinos and the people involved, as the animals can become stressed and unpredictable during transport. To minimize these risks, wildlife vets carefully monitor the health of the rhinos before, during and after the move.

Name: Giraffe Rodeo - Saving Giraffes from Extinction: Wildlife Vets on a Relocation Mission
Overview:
Wildlife vets relocate giraffes to different reserves for population management, genetic diversity and to prevent inbreeding.

The process is challenging and dangerous for both the giraffes and the wildlife vets, as giraffes are large, heavy animals and can easily become stressed during transportation.

It is important to monitor the health of the giraffes during the relocation process to ensure they are not injured. Regular check-ups of the giraffes' vital signs, such as heart rate and temperature, are necessary to ensure their well-being during transportation.

Name: Wild Animal Fight: Hyenas and Vultures Compete for a Hippo Carcass
Overview:
A cackle of spotted hyena fights off vultures over a hippo carcass in the Masai Mara, Kenya.

Like vultures, hyenas are also scavengers and depend on the remains of dead animals for food. However, one unique aspect of hyenas is that they can kill their own prey, unlike vultures which only feed on already dead animals.

Competition between hyenas and vultures over carrion is a common occurrence in the wild. During this competition, hyenas use their strength and powerful jaws to fight off vultures and take control of the carcass.

Name: Vultures vs Vultures: Fight Over Carcass
Overview:
Vultures fight each other over the remains of a hippo carcass in Kenya.

Vultures, being scavengers, feed on the remains of dead animals, and access to this food source can be limited. As a result, competition amongst vultures over carrion can occur. This competition can be fierce and violent, with birds pushing, pecking and clawing at each other in order to gain access to food.

The unique adaptation of vultures is their bald head, which helps them dissipate heat but also aids in keeping their head clean while fighting and eating, since no feathers would get stuck in the blood and remains. Additionally, vultures have strong, sharp beaks and talons that they use to tear at carrion and fend off rivals.

Name: Maggots vs Warthog Carcass in South Africa
Overview: Maggots infest and devour the remains of a warthog carcass in South Africa

Name: Eagle Fumbles the (Eye) Ball
Overview: A tawny eagle plucks an eyeball out of a recently killed kudu. When the eagle drops the eyeball, a yellow-billed kite spots it and swoops down to steal it. The skin of recently killed antelope is too tough for raptors to penetrate, thus restricting them to soft parts such as eyes and entrails, while they wait for larger scavengers like lions and hyenas to tear the skin open and expose the meat.

Name: Lions Feeding - No Volunteers to Stand Closer
Overview: A pride of lions is viewed from above their feeding ground.

Name: Scavenger Birds Raid Pilot Whale Carcasses in the Falkland Islands
Overview:
Scavenger birds including dolphin gulls, striated caracaras, southern giant petrel, kelp gulls and turkey vultures raid a mass of 30 pilot whale carcasses, beached in the Falkland Islands.

0:00 - kelp gulls
0:07 - dolphin gull and Kelp gulls
0:09 - dolphin gull
0:15 - striated caracara
0:21 - turkey vultures
0:43 - southern giant petrel

Name: Leopard Lunch Curbside Pickup
Overview:
The leopard featured here is one of two donated to a wildlife preserve for rehabilitation and release into the wild. This leopard investigates and ultimately drags an impala back to the relative safety of the bush inside a reintroduction boma at a wildlife reserve in South Africa.

This subspecies is the African leopard. Ranging from Morocco throughout most of sub-Saharan Africa, it is the most widespread type of leopard in the world. A leopard's fur is generally soft and thick, notably softer on the belly than on the back. Its hair color varies between individuals, from pale yellow to dark golden with dark spots grouped in rosettes. Normally solitary animals, adults associate only during the mating season.

Name: Wildlife Rangers Rescue Wildebeest Caught in Snare
Overview: Wildlife rangers in the Masai Mara of Kenya rescue a wildebeest caught in a snare.  Poaching and bushmeat hunting are increasing rapidly in the Serengeti and the Masai Mara, where wildlife populations and habitats are declining at an alarming rate.  Wildebeest are important in the ecosystem and they are often seen with other grazing animals such as zebra and antelope. Every year, the "great wildebeest migration" consists of more than one million wildebeest that follow the rain patterns between Kenya and Tanzania. They help guide other species to water and food. Wildebeest are considered one of the most important keystone species in Africa’s ecosystems and without them the entire ecosystem will collapse.

Name: Striated Caracaras Find and Compete for a Dead Penguin
Overview: A curious caracara gives a camera a close-up inspection before joining its peers in competition for the meat of a penguin chick that had died in a nearby nesting colony.

Name: Return to the Meat Locker - Jackal Eats Impala Eyeball
Overview: A black-backed jackal returns to an impala carcass to eat the leftovers -- an eyeball and drumstick to go.

Name: Using Dart Guns to Save Elephants
Overview: Dr. Will Fowlds of Amakhala Game Reserve pursues a matriarch near a wildlife lodge to dart her with a birth control vaccine.  Elephant birth control is an effective means at controlling populations before they get too large or out of balance.  Wildlife reserves practice active population management using immunocontraception. Many reserves have seen effective population growth reductions of at least 50%.

Name: Rangers Rescue a Snared Wildebeest
Overview: Rangers on an anti-poaching patrol rescue a wildebeest from a poacher’s snare.  The use of snares by commercial poachers is an existential threat to wildlife throughout much of the developing world.  An estimated 12 million animals are killed yearly to feed a growing demand for “bush meat” which is considered a delicacy by growing urban populations surrounding parks and animal sanctuaries.

Name: Frightened Wildebeest Charges Rescue Rangers
Overview:
Rangers in Kenya's Masai Mara National Park risk injury as a snared wildebeest fights them off.

Hunting for plains game with snares is common in the Mara Triangle. However, these indiscriminate traps capture everything from tiny dik-dik to massive elephants.

Name: Return to the Meat Locker - Slender Mongoose
Overview: A slender mongoose returns to an impala carcass for more to eat, disregarding the many flies.

Name: Male Lion Feasts on a Massive Elephant Carcass
Overview: Africa's iconic predator, the lion, feasts on an African elephant in the Masai Mara of Kenya.  Lions are apex predators, as they help regulate the populations of other animals such as herbivores and other species. If one prey species becomes too abundant, it can make an entire ecosystem unhealthy. Grasses and other food will become less abundant for all other species to thrive.  Scientists believe that healthy predator populations help maintain functioning ecosystems.

Name: Ingenious Method to Load Elephants
Overview: Wildlife vets use a 32-ton crane to load anesthetized elephants into a relocation truck.

Name: Marabou Stork Battles Ruppell's Vultures over Kudu Carcass
Overview:
A marabou stork defends a kudu carcass from waves of Ruppell's vultures vying for a meal. 

The name marabou is thought to be derived from the Arabic word "mur," meaning hermit-like. The marabou stork is unmistakable due to its size, bare head and neck, black back and white underparts. It has a huge bill, a pink gular sac at its throat, a neck ruff and black legs and wings. The species is known to be quite ill-tempered, perhaps giving rise to its colorful name.

Name: Vultures Feed on Wildebeest
Overview: The competition is fierce as vultures and a marabou stork skirmish to feed on the carcass of a wildebeest near Maasai Mara, Kenya.

Name: Loading a Giant Sleeping Elephant
Overview: Wildlife vets transport an elephant using an innovative technique, which keeps the elephant suspended and upright.

Name: Saving Rhinos with Helicopters
Overview: A black rhino is moved by helicopter to a safe place to help protect it from poaching.  While it looks strange to see a rhino hanging upside down, it is a quicker mode of transportation when there are no roads to accommodate transport trucks.  The rhinos are tranquilized, blindfolded and ear plugged to minimize sensations.  While hanging them upside down may be the easiest way to transport them, scientific studies have also determined that this allows more oxygen exchange compared to hanging them in a “lying sideways” position.  But even transporting upside-down has its challenges. Here, a tranquilizer dart becomes lodged into the skin upon landing.

Name: Vultures Fight Over a Carcass
Overview:
Size matters. King vultures push around smaller black vultures as they both scramble for the last bits of a carcass in Costa Rica.

This video was collected in collaboration with Osa Conservation, a nonprofit organization dedicated to protecting the globally significant biodiversity of the Osa Peninsula, Costa Rica.

Name: Wildlife Vets Help Save White Rhinos with Helicopters
Overview: Veterinary medical teams use helicopters to locate and dart white rhinos that are being sedated so their horns can be removed to remove the incentive for poachers to kill them.

Name: Vulture's Tear Apart Carcass
Overview:
Chaos ensues on the carcass of an African buffalo.

Ruppell's vultures are highly adapted to eating carcass meat, hide and even bones as seen here in this feeding frenzy. The birds have specialized tongues with backward-facing spikes to help tear flesh from bone and to not leave even the tiniest piece behind.

Ruppell's vultures are also considered to be the highest-flying bird, reaching altitudes of 11,300 m (37,000 ft) above sea level ... cruising altitude for many commercial jets. Their species are in steep decline, however, and are listed as endangered due to habitat loss and incidental poisonings.

Name: Decomposing Norway Rat Visited by Beetles and Squirrel
Overview:
A pine squirrel investigates the carcass of a Norway rat as margined burying beetles crawl across the carrion during the early stages of decomposition.

Squirrels, like many of their rodent relations, are surprisingly omnivorous. In addition to their familiar diet of nuts and seeds, squirrels are scavengers by nature and have been known to eat carrion. By contrast, the margined burying beetle feeds almost exclusively on decaying animals. These insects use their sensitive antennae to locate rotting flesh. Once found, they will proceed to devour the material and in some cases, cover it with the surrounding substrate, resulting in accelerated decomposition of the carcass.

Name: Wildlife Vets Perform Autopsy on Poached Rhino
Overview: This white rhino was killed by poachers on a wildlife reserve in South Africa. Unfortunately, the poachers escaped into the bush before wildlife rangers could intervene. Since the poachers were unable to remove the horn, the wildlife vets must now perform forensics and an autopsy to search for any signs that may lead them to the poachers.

Name: Reaching Into a Rhino
Overview: Wildlife veterinarian, Dr. Will Fowlds, and his medical team work to save a female white rhinoceros that has been gored by another rhino in South Africa.  In a series of visits, Dr. Fowlds goes to extreme measures to treat the rhino’s wounds that penetrate deep into her shoulder and side. Infection and organ failure threaten this mother even after she survives the original attack.

Name: Saving the Cutest Cheetah
Overview: These wildlife vets at Kwandwe Game Reserve track down and dart an entire cheetah family to save the life of one young cub.  After capturing the young cub and taking some in-field x-rays, it is discovered that the cheetah cub has a broken hind leg.  To keep the family together while they fix the leg, the vets must capture each cheetah before they stray too far.  It is important to save cheetah in the wild because their populations are decreasing.

Name: Hyena Feasting on Antelope
Overview: Spotted hyenas feast on a blesbok antelope before being released onto the Dinokeng reserve where hyenas had previously been eliminated. Biologists call this reintroduction of a species into its previous habit "rewilding." Rewilding can be an important conservation tool for conserving an endangered species.

Name: Dead Hippo Explodes Guts Everywhere
Overview:
A bloated hippo floats in a river and gets devoured by crocodiles.

Hippos are the third-largest land mammal and weigh approximately 3,000 pounds. While many crocodiles prey upon other animals, they frequently scavenge dead carrion. Crocs also have the most acidic stomach of any vertebrate and can easily digest horns, hooves, bones and hides.

Name: African Birds of Prey Scavenge Dead Kudu
Overview: Birds of prey at a waterhole in Zimbabwe descend upon a recently killed kudu, initiating a feeding frenzy. Vultures, yellow-billed kites, tawny eagles, marabou storks and pied crows all squawk and scramble to get in on the feast - a perfect example of what is known as "scramble competition."

Name: How to Save Elephants Preemptively
Overview: Wildlife Vets administer birth-control vaccines to elephant herds which are getting too large for the land to support.  While elephants may be a threatened species in many places, some elephant populations can get too large for wildlife reserves to adequately handle.  When these populations get too big, elephants will expand their territories. This can often lead to human wildlife conflicts that can turn deadly for humans and for elephants.

Name: Vet Darts a White Rhino
Overview: A veterinarian and his assistants dart a white rhino named Binkie to update and charge the tracking collar on its ankle. This procedure helps rangers track the white rhino, making rhino poaching more difficult.

Name: Rhino Dehorning - Protection Against Poachers
Overview:
Veterinarians dehorn a rhino to protect it from poaching. 

Dehorning rhinos may reduce their susceptibility to poaching as they are killed only for their horns. Rhino horn, the same material as human fingernails, gets ground up and sold on the black market for more than the price of gold.

Name: How to Move an Elephant
Overview: Dr. Will Fowlds and his veterinary team move an African elephant to a nearby wildlife reserve.  Using a new technique for capturing animals, they suspend the elephant and load it with a crane while it is  fully anesthetized, allowing it to wake gradually and safely inside the transport container.

Name: Secret Rhino Relocation
Overview: A group of wildlife vets move dozens of rhinos under the cover of darkness.

Name: Vultures Feed on Wildebeest (Extended)
Overview: A wake of Ruppell's vultures devour a kudu carcass as a marabou stork attempts to get in on the action. The feast comes to a temporary halt when a bonded pair of lappet-faced vultures swoop in to grab their fill.

Name: Striped Marlin Showdown - 360° Baitball Experience
Overview:
Striped marlin hunt a bait-ball of fish off the coast of Baja, Mexico.

Striped marlin, famed for their strategic hunting of bait-balls, often work in groups to drive prey like anchovies or sardines towards the surface or shore. They use their bills to spear fish and can manipulate their appearance for added camouflage. When feeding, their colors transform into vivid and eye-catching hues, often displaying vibrant blues, greens and metallic sheens.

Name: Watch Giant River Otters frolic in the Northern Pantanal Region of Brazil
Overview:
Giant river otters playing outside of their den in the northern Pantanal region of Brazil.

Giant river otters are the largest freshwater otters in the world, growing up to 6 feet in length. They are also an endangered species found primarily in South America, specifically in the Amazon, Orinoco, and La Plata river basins.

They are a highly social species, living in family groups with strong bonds between members. They are also known for their vocalizations and use a wide range of sounds to communicate with each other.

This video is in 8k

Name: Leggy Love Fest: Witness the Oklahoma Brown Tarantula Mating Migration
Overview:
Follow the Oklahoma brown tarantulas' annual mating trek through Colorado's Comanche National Grasslands.

While commonly referred to as a tarantula migration, this phenomenon is actually a 'mate-gration,' where adult males leave their burrows and travel significant distances in search of females for mating.  During this event, many biologists study the tarantulas to help uncover the importance of their conservation. The tarantulas also attract so much attention during this event that the local town of La Junta comes alive with a 'Tarantula Festival,' celebrating these eight-legged wonders.

This video is in 5.7k

Name: Screaming Symphony: Tasmanian Devil Harmony
Overview:
Two tasmanian devils scream and square off over a dead rabbit.

Known for their spine-chilling vocalizations, tasmanian devils scream when they feel threatened or want to communicate. They also have voracious appetites and can devour up to 40% of their body weight in just 30 minutes.  Among the animal kingdom they have the strongest bite, pound-for-pound, rivaling that of a crocodile.

Name: Possum Pandemonium: Brushing Up On Australia's Brushtail Wonders
Overview:
Two brushtail possums in the outback strike defensive poses over a cache of food.

Brushtail possums have complex social structures, forming small family groups that collaborate and sometimes share resources and territories. Beyond physical mimicry, their communication involves scent-marking through specialized glands, conveying vital information about territory and reproductive status. They also have a prehensile tail that acts as a fifth limb for balance, gripping and communication.

Name: Hoppy Hour : Grey Kangaroo Antics and Insights
Overview:
Grey kangaroos hop around the Australian outback.

These kangaroos are known for their incredible hopping abilities. With robust hind legs and a specially adapted tail, they are true masters of mobility. Their powerful tails serve as a counterbalance for stability during their impressive leaps. Built for speed and endurance, grey kangaroos can cover up to 8 meters in a single hop, reaching speeds of around 56 kilometers per hour.

Name: Koala Konundrums: Insights Into the Lives of Australia's Tree Dwellers
Overview:
A cute koala sits and scratches in a eucalyptus tree.

Koalas spend up to 20 hours a day napping in trees. Their low metabolic rate allows them to thrive on a not particularly energy-rich diet. Given that koalas only consume just a few of more than 700 species of eucalyptus trees, scientists consider them selective eaters. The IUCN currently lists koalas as a vulnerable species, as their populations are decreasing.

Name: Down Under’s Mini Macropods: The Science and Reproductive Strategies of Pademelons
Overview:
A pademelon and her baby hop through the forest in Australia.

Pademelons are marsupials with remarkable reproductive strategies. Learn how these tiny kangaroo cousins postpone embryo development until food is plentiful, use a pouch as a nursery and juggle multiple joeys.

Name: Echidna Extravaganza: Exploring the Quirks and Quills from the Land Down Under
Overview:
A short-beaked echidna explores its surroundings in the Australian bush.

Short-beaked echidnas belong to the ancient lineage of monotremes, or egg-laying mammals. Their spiky quills help protect the animals from predation. In addition, they inhabit a diversity of landscapes—from dense forests to open grasslands and rocky terrains.

Name: Kangaroo Cousins: Hopping with Wallabies in the Outback
Overview:
Wallabies hop, skip and jump around the Australian Outback.

Often dubbed “mini” kangaroos, wallabies share family ties with kangaroos. Wallabies are smaller and tend to live in forested areas compared to the open grasslands of their larger counterparts. Australia has around 30 wallaby species, each with unique fur patterns for camouflage among a variety of habitats.
